WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:10.050 --> 00:00:13.200
&gt;&gt; Betsy Peterson: To kick
us off I introduce myself.

00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:15.060
I'm Betsy Peterson,
I'm the director

00:00:15.060 --> 00:00:17.270
of the American Folklife Center.

00:00:17.270 --> 00:00:18.820
And on behalf of
the staff I want

00:00:18.820 --> 00:00:21.060
to welcome everyone here today.

00:00:21.060 --> 00:00:24.240
This is the latest and
actually the last event

00:00:24.240 --> 00:00:28.030
of the fiscal year in our
Botkin Lecture series.

00:00:28.030 --> 00:00:32.350
And it's a very special
one I think.

00:00:32.350 --> 00:00:36.610
It's called Since '68: Cultural
Organizations Programming

00:00:36.610 --> 00:00:39.790
Documentation and
Community Enrichment.

00:00:39.790 --> 00:00:43.170
And we've done a few events
throughout the year focusing

00:00:43.170 --> 00:00:51.370
on events and movements, etc.,
related to 1968 and beyond.

00:00:51.370 --> 00:00:53.370
And so this is one of them.

00:00:53.370 --> 00:00:55.970
The Botkin series is
an opportunity for us

00:00:55.970 --> 00:01:00.860
to present the very best
in folk life scholarship,

00:01:00.860 --> 00:01:05.400
ethnomusicology, oral history,
and other related fields.

00:01:05.400 --> 00:01:06.830
And to share them with you.

00:01:06.830 --> 00:01:12.640
It's also an opportunity for
us to enrich our own archives.

00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:15.330
All of these events
are tape recorded,

00:01:15.330 --> 00:01:18.460
or video recorded I should
say, and will make their way

00:01:18.460 --> 00:01:23.160
into our archives and also make
their way online eventually.

00:01:23.160 --> 00:01:28.500
So with that said, please turn
off cell phones, if you would.

00:01:28.500 --> 00:01:30.350
I'd appreciate it.

00:01:30.350 --> 00:01:35.120
And one last thing, I just
want to say I'm so happy

00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:38.270
that this is happening.

00:01:38.270 --> 00:01:41.340
We have three organizations,
nonprofits,

00:01:41.340 --> 00:01:45.160
started in the late 1960's.

00:01:45.160 --> 00:01:51.070
Icons of cultural programming
of cultural work at a time

00:01:51.070 --> 00:01:55.780
when nonprofits were just really
kind of getting their foothold.

00:01:55.780 --> 00:01:58.590
And before the 1970's
when nonprofits,

00:01:58.590 --> 00:02:02.180
cultural nonprofits all
nonprofits exploded.

00:02:02.180 --> 00:02:05.620
It tripled, quadrupled
in the United States.

00:02:05.620 --> 00:02:07.430
These folks were
there at the beginning

00:02:07.430 --> 00:02:12.500
and these folks were figuring
out what the templates were.

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:15.020
Figuring out how to
work with communities

00:02:15.020 --> 00:02:18.990
and present what they
needed and wanted.

00:02:18.990 --> 00:02:20.640
And so I'm really pleased

00:02:20.640 --> 00:02:23.720
that we have these
organizations with us today.

00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:25.650
They deserve our thanks.

00:02:25.650 --> 00:02:27.540
And so to tell you
a little bit more

00:02:27.540 --> 00:02:31.920
about what this is I'm going to
turn this over to John Fen now.

00:02:31.920 --> 00:02:34.090
But mainly I just
wanted to get up here

00:02:34.090 --> 00:02:42.250
and say I think it's really
great that it's happening.

00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:43.870
&gt;&gt; John Fenn: Thank
you very much, Betsy.

00:02:43.870 --> 00:02:45.760
So greetings and
welcome to everyone.

00:02:45.760 --> 00:02:47.060
My name is John Fen.

00:02:47.060 --> 00:02:48.460
I'm the head of research
and programs

00:02:48.460 --> 00:02:50.990
for the American Folklife Center
at the Library of Congress.

00:02:50.990 --> 00:02:54.000
I'd like to extend thanks to
all of you in the audience,

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:56.390
all the staff at the library
who are working in support

00:02:56.390 --> 00:02:59.920
of this event, and of
course our panelists.

00:02:59.920 --> 00:03:02.380
Across these two panels we'll
hear from individuals involved

00:03:02.380 --> 00:03:04.590
with three cultural
organizations that launched in

00:03:04.590 --> 00:03:07.070
or shortly thereafter 1968.

00:03:07.070 --> 00:03:09.030
Each of these organizations
anchor their activities

00:03:09.030 --> 00:03:11.170
in community, culture,
and identity.

00:03:11.170 --> 00:03:13.250
Rooting their menus of
programs and services

00:03:13.250 --> 00:03:16.610
in the places stories and
heritages that surrounded them.

00:03:16.610 --> 00:03:19.040
The idea for these panels
took shape via broader staff

00:03:19.040 --> 00:03:23.250
discussions about 1968 and the
watershed of cultural activity

00:03:23.250 --> 00:03:25.300
that emerged from that time.

00:03:25.300 --> 00:03:26.930
Noting that the Center
for Traditional Music

00:03:26.930 --> 00:03:29.070
and Dance celebrating
its 50th year

00:03:29.070 --> 00:03:31.390
and that Appalshop is
getting ready to do the same.

00:03:31.390 --> 00:03:34.310
We began thinking about
the roles of organizations

00:03:34.310 --> 00:03:36.840
and what they've done in terms
of supporting cultural heritage.

00:03:36.840 --> 00:03:40.480
From documenting to presenting,
training to advocating.

00:03:40.480 --> 00:03:43.200
During the past 50 years
cultural organizations have

00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:46.260
operated as vital resources
and spaces for communities.

00:03:46.260 --> 00:03:48.380
Such organizations have
taken a range of shapes

00:03:48.380 --> 00:03:50.210
and the three we'll
explore today began

00:03:50.210 --> 00:03:54.140
as an ethnic art center, a media
collective, and a bookstore.

00:03:54.140 --> 00:03:57.570
CTMD, Appalshop, and Drum
and Spear respectively.

00:03:57.570 --> 00:03:59.600
The structure of each panel
