00:04:46.620 --> 00:04:53.110
Martin Koenig: You
know, it was --

00:04:53.110 --> 00:04:58.550
the 60's were such a
different time in the states.

00:04:58.550 --> 00:05:00.500
I guess in the world.

00:05:00.500 --> 00:05:08.800
But here, the whole emerging art
scene really started taking off.

00:05:08.800 --> 00:05:12.900
And it is so different
from today.

00:05:12.900 --> 00:05:18.680
So for instance, the concept

00:05:18.680 --> 00:05:23.830
of a Balkan Arts
Center occurred prior

00:05:23.830 --> 00:05:27.020
to its technical launching.

00:05:27.020 --> 00:05:31.000
So Ethel and I are
constantly arm wrestling

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:34.410
about when the Balkan
Arts Center started

00:05:34.410 --> 00:05:38.490
because there is no specific
date that it technically --

00:05:38.490 --> 00:05:43.650
well yes, there is a technical
date, which is in 1973.

00:05:43.650 --> 00:05:47.530
That was the time that
we went to a lawyer

00:05:47.530 --> 00:05:50.420
and they drew up the papers.

00:05:50.420 --> 00:05:54.060
But part of that is because
even the federal government just

00:05:54.060 --> 00:05:59.990
started funding the arts
through NEA in the mid 60's.

00:05:59.990 --> 00:06:04.430
New York State started funding
in later than that, I believe,

00:06:04.430 --> 00:06:06.840
or approximately the same time.

00:06:06.840 --> 00:06:14.060
Folk arts divisions
got started even later.

00:06:14.060 --> 00:06:18.560
So it wasn't on either
my radar screen,

00:06:18.560 --> 00:06:22.690
or I think Ethel's,
anything about that.

00:06:22.690 --> 00:06:27.930
But the concept of Balkan
Arts Center started earlier.

00:06:27.930 --> 00:06:34.190
For me, I went to Bulgaria and
the Balkans to do research.

00:06:34.190 --> 00:06:37.560
I fell in love with
the dance form.

00:06:37.560 --> 00:06:41.480
And basically the first time
of the Balkan Arts Center,

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:43.570
the first stage of
the Balkan Art Center,

00:06:43.570 --> 00:06:49.770
was devoted to research
and documentation,

00:06:49.770 --> 00:06:53.660
and ultimately presentation
and publication,

00:06:53.660 --> 00:06:57.320
which is what we
basically have always done,

00:06:57.320 --> 00:07:00.240
but it was directed
towards Balkan dancing.

00:07:00.240 --> 00:07:04.630
And for that I had a 501C3,
which was Margaret Mead,

00:07:04.630 --> 00:07:07.260
the Institute for
Intercultural Studies.

00:07:07.260 --> 00:07:11.790
So is Margaret Mead who
somebody wanted to give me $200

00:07:11.790 --> 00:07:14.310
to help me on my
research in Bulgaria.

00:07:14.310 --> 00:07:17.540
They made a contribution
to the Institute

00:07:17.540 --> 00:07:19.440
for Intercultural Studies

00:07:19.440 --> 00:07:23.130
and then Margaret Mead would
send me a check for $200.

00:07:23.130 --> 00:07:25.590
And that happened through 1973.

00:07:25.590 --> 00:07:31.920
And in 1973 -- or in
1972 I think it was,

00:07:31.920 --> 00:07:38.160
the expansion arts program from
NEA gave, not Balkan Art Center,

00:07:38.160 --> 00:07:39.460
but the Institute

00:07:39.460 --> 00:07:41.610
for Intercultural
Studies a $5,000 grant,

00:07:41.610 --> 00:07:46.060
which was then subcontracted
to the Balkan Arts Center.

00:07:46.060 --> 00:07:47.440
And she said, "Well you've got

00:07:47.440 --> 00:07:51.140
to form your own organization
now because your money is going

00:07:51.140 --> 00:07:54.820
to be coming in and you're
going to expand your program."

00:07:54.820 --> 00:07:59.240
So the first stage of the
Balkan Arts Center was devoted

00:07:59.240 --> 00:08:01.830
towards dance.

00:08:01.830 --> 00:08:07.340
And I can say from the very
beginning to where it's at now

00:08:07.340 --> 00:08:09.350
that -- and I am
no longer working

00:08:09.350 --> 00:08:11.870
with the Balkan Arts
Center but I'd been

00:08:11.870 --> 00:08:16.610
on the board all the way
through, which is now the CTMD.

00:08:16.610 --> 00:08:21.280
That it changed in 1970
when Ethel and I --

00:08:21.280 --> 00:08:25.100
Ethel invited me to join
her to work with her

00:08:25.100 --> 00:08:29.540
at the Smithsonian Institution
Festival American Folklife.

00:08:29.540 --> 00:08:37.570
And that was where it expanded
from dance into communities.

00:08:37.570 --> 00:08:40.830
And I had been doing five years
of field research in communities

00:08:40.830 --> 00:08:44.510
in the Balkans, coming back
to the states and meeting

00:08:44.510 --> 00:08:48.410
with families who were
hyphenated Americans here

00:08:48.410 --> 00:08:51.880
in New York City,
and getting a sense

00:08:51.880 --> 00:08:54.910
of what the communities
were here.

00:08:54.910 --> 00:08:59.820
And coming with the sense
where the organization,

00:08:59.820 --> 00:09:02.010
from the beginning,
was about community.

00:09:02.010 --> 00:09:03.870
Was about building community.

00:09:03.870 --> 00:09:06.420
Was about strengthening
community.

00:09:06.420 --> 00:09:10.060
And the cement of all that
was the music the songs

00:09:10.060 --> 00:09:12.150
and the dances.

00:09:12.150 --> 00:09:20.590
And I think those four years
between '70 and '75, '74 we --

00:09:20.590 --> 00:09:22.490
I think would not
be an exaggeration

00:09:22.490 --> 00:09:25.310
that we spent seven
days a week together.

00:09:25.310 --> 00:09:30.910
Sometimes up to 18 hours
a day together constantly

00:09:30.910 --> 00:09:32.530
in these conversations.

00:09:32.530 --> 00:09:34.580
Constantly working
in different cities.

00:09:34.580 --> 00:09:36.440
Constantly working with
different families.

00:09:36.440 --> 00:09:38.160
Constantly being in
church basements.

00:09:38.160 --> 00:09:42.390
Constantly in traveling and
the Smithsonian was really

00:09:42.390 --> 00:09:44.440
that gave us the opportunity.

00:09:44.440 --> 00:09:49.230
That festival gave us the
opportunity to develop a model

00:09:49.230 --> 00:09:54.740
that was serviceable for the
Balkan Art Center and we took it

00:09:54.740 --> 00:09:59.810
and we kept going with that
model in how to do this work.

00:09:59.810 --> 00:10:04.090
I think the next stage from
that would be in the late 70's

00:10:04.090 --> 00:10:08.300
where we started doing
some tours and performances

00:10:08.300 --> 00:10:11.260
with Jewish, Italian, Irish.

00:10:11.260 --> 00:10:13.420
And we'd be asked,
"Balkan Art Center?

00:10:13.420 --> 00:10:16.240
What does that got
to do with me?"

00:10:16.240 --> 00:10:20.630
And we've been struggling
with names all along the way,

00:10:20.630 --> 00:10:24.800
and that's where he came up
with the Ethnic Folk Art Center.

00:10:24.800 --> 00:10:28.160
And eventually we came
-- still trying to --

00:10:28.160 --> 00:10:30.250
that didn't quite
say it where CTMD,

00:10:30.250 --> 00:10:33.450
Center for Traditional
Music and Dance came in.

00:10:33.450 --> 00:10:35.100
And the next stage.

00:10:35.100 --> 00:10:39.490
So the the stage in the 70's
and early 80's, mid 80's was

00:10:39.490 --> 00:10:43.640
that it was still dealing with
European ethnic traditions.

00:10:43.640 --> 00:10:49.080
And then there was a change in
the terrain that we were able

00:10:49.080 --> 00:10:52.360
to go and work with all ethnic
communities, which is something

00:10:52.360 --> 00:10:54.800
that we always wanted to do.

00:10:54.800 --> 00:10:58.920
But the thinking was it could
happen at that point and I think

00:10:58.920 --> 00:11:01.550
that really represents
the center which Pete

00:11:01.550 --> 00:11:04.690
and Ethel will talk about.

00:11:04.690 --> 00:11:09.650
That all ethnic communities
were embraced by the center

00:11:09.650 --> 00:11:14.260
because the story is basically
the same with variations.

00:11:14.260 --> 00:11:18.420
Anyway, I just wanted to
frame it in that way .

00:11:18.420 --> 00:11:20.080
And I think the other
interesting thing

00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:23.490
about this is Ethel and I are
both children of immigrants.

00:11:23.490 --> 00:11:26.950
And immigrant music,
immigrant societies here,

00:11:26.950 --> 00:11:34.120
we thought in the same way
politically with a small pea

00:11:34.120 --> 00:11:37.010
to embrace and champion
those forms.

00:11:37.010 --> 00:11:40.270
And it is interesting, we were
talking last night well nobody

00:11:40.270 --> 00:11:44.000
really worked with
that up until the 60's.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:49.250
So what we did with this
organization and are still doing

00:11:49.250 --> 00:11:58.240
under Pete's leadership is
continuing to broaden the scope

00:11:58.240 --> 00:12:01.860
of what's being done
and creating a model.

00:12:01.860 --> 00:12:04.580
Because there was no model for
us in the work that we did.

00:12:04.580 --> 00:12:07.710
And the reason we spent all
that time was there was nobody

00:12:07.710 --> 00:12:11.750
to refer to and we were
creating something.

