00:29:23.860 --> 00:29:27.640
in the production
rooms recording sound,

00:29:27.640 --> 00:29:31.110
shooting the cameras, editing.

00:29:31.110 --> 00:29:32.410
You know, all of the
work that it took

00:29:32.410 --> 00:29:41.300
to make the films were mainly
urban people in big cities.

00:29:41.300 --> 00:29:44.270
And we were in this
small town which I've --

00:29:44.270 --> 00:29:46.290
okay we got this
equipment, now what can we do

00:29:46.290 --> 00:29:47.590
with that that's different

00:29:47.590 --> 00:29:50.350
from what those other
people were doing with it.

00:29:50.350 --> 00:29:51.650
And of course one of the things

00:29:51.650 --> 00:29:59.020
that became obvious right
off the bat was that we felt

00:29:59.020 --> 00:30:06.730
like somehow the television
portrayals of us were wrong.

00:30:06.730 --> 00:30:09.480
Like when Appalshop started
there was Beverly Hillbillies

00:30:09.480 --> 00:30:15.320
on the television, Hee
Haw, Green Acres, you know,

00:30:15.320 --> 00:30:17.470
all of the Hollywood stuff.

00:30:17.470 --> 00:30:19.950
Li'l Abner, all the cartoons.

00:30:19.950 --> 00:30:22.110
And there was just
a open ridicule

00:30:22.110 --> 00:30:25.330
of our people in the media.

00:30:25.330 --> 00:30:31.930
And so we thought, "Well
we have a job to do.

00:30:31.930 --> 00:30:33.780
We got to set this right."

00:30:33.780 --> 00:30:39.580
So we -- so they started calling
it Community Film Workshop

00:30:39.580 --> 00:30:40.880
Council of Appalachian.

00:30:40.880 --> 00:30:42.180
And we said, "No, no, no.

00:30:42.180 --> 00:30:45.050
We'll call it Appalachian
Film Workshop."

00:30:45.050 --> 00:30:47.770
And then we did that
for a few months

00:30:47.770 --> 00:30:49.950
and then we said,
"That's too long.

00:30:49.950 --> 00:30:53.540
We'll just leave out the
achian, the film, and the work.

00:30:53.540 --> 00:30:57.000
And we're kind of
like Appalshop."

00:30:57.000 --> 00:30:59.570
And that's what we did.

00:30:59.570 --> 00:31:05.720
And so we formed our own
little Board of Directors

00:31:05.720 --> 00:31:10.130
and then sure enough -- so what
had happened was Community Film

00:31:10.130 --> 00:31:12.750
Workshop Council was
funded by the Office

00:31:12.750 --> 00:31:15.040
of Economic Opportunity.

00:31:15.040 --> 00:31:17.230
So who's got that?

00:31:17.230 --> 00:31:18.900
Office of Economic Opportunity.

00:31:18.900 --> 00:31:22.540
OEO. You all have heard of that?

00:31:22.540 --> 00:31:24.440
So it was the war on poverty.

00:31:24.440 --> 00:31:26.980
There's the agency
created by LBJ

00:31:26.980 --> 00:31:30.040
to spearhead the war
on poverty, right.

00:31:30.040 --> 00:31:36.920
And so start thinking
for a second.

00:31:36.920 --> 00:31:39.030
We started in '69.

00:31:39.030 --> 00:31:42.230
LBJ is not the president
anymore, right.

00:31:42.230 --> 00:31:44.060
Nixon's elected in ,68.

00:31:44.060 --> 00:31:47.650
Takes office in January '69.

00:31:47.650 --> 00:31:49.120
Well they start putting
pressure,

00:31:49.120 --> 00:31:52.690
the Nixon administration on
Community Film Workshop Council

00:31:52.690 --> 00:31:55.150
in New York City
saying, "We are okay

00:31:55.150 --> 00:31:57.980
with the vocational
education side of this

00:31:57.980 --> 00:32:02.520
but this community based
expression stuff, we don't like.

00:32:02.520 --> 00:32:05.580
And who knows, they
might be making films

00:32:05.580 --> 00:32:07.990
against strip mining, or
they might want to kind

00:32:07.990 --> 00:32:10.620
of like have mine
safety, or they want

00:32:10.620 --> 00:32:14.270
to prevent black lung disease,
or all this other stuff

00:32:14.270 --> 00:32:15.860
that they'd be making
films about."

00:32:15.860 --> 00:32:21.370
So Nixon administration
wasn't going to have it.

00:32:21.370 --> 00:32:25.940
So then we split off with the
New York people and we said,

00:32:25.940 --> 00:32:27.600
"We'll just go our
own separate way."

00:32:27.600 --> 00:32:28.900
Which we did in '71.

00:32:28.900 --> 00:32:33.000
Anyway, that's kind
of how we started.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:34.380
It was kind of a wild ride

00:32:34.380 --> 00:32:37.050
but we were pretty political
right off the bat in the sense

00:32:37.050 --> 00:32:41.430
of knowing that we were
in a tumultuous time.

00:32:41.430 --> 00:32:46.740
People getting killed, city's
going up in smoke, Vietnam War.

00:32:46.740 --> 00:32:50.650
And we felt like there
should be a voice

00:32:50.650 --> 00:32:53.260
from the coal fields
of Appalachia.

00:32:53.260 --> 00:32:57.890
And we tried to be that.

00:32:57.890 --> 00:32:59.190
&gt;&gt; Alexander Gibson: Yeah

00:32:59.190 --> 00:33:01.800
and I think there's a
couple other unique pieces

00:33:01.800 --> 00:33:03.190
of the beginning of Appalshop.

00:33:03.190 --> 00:33:04.490
My name is Alex.

00:33:04.490 --> 00:33:08.220
I've been with Appalshop
for about four years now.

00:33:08.220 --> 00:33:11.590
I come from eastern Kentucky
from tobacco country.

00:33:11.590 --> 00:33:17.050
Which is about an hour and a
half, probably 45 minutes away

00:33:17.050 --> 00:33:20.470
from Whitesburg if we
could sprout wings.

00:33:20.470 --> 00:33:23.680
But because the way the
mountains go, it takes probably

00:33:23.680 --> 00:33:25.760
about two hours to get there.

00:33:25.760 --> 00:33:28.010
And it's tobacco country
instead of coal country,

00:33:28.010 --> 00:33:32.170
which doesn't seem significant
if you're not from the area

00:33:32.170 --> 00:33:37.080
but it's pretty big culturally
different sort of thing.

00:33:37.080 --> 00:33:39.610
There's a couple other pieces
about Appalshop's founding

00:33:39.610 --> 00:33:41.160
that I find unique
because it's, you know,

00:33:41.160 --> 00:33:42.460
it's been here for 50 years.

00:33:42.460 --> 00:33:46.640
So when Appalshop moved
in and Herb E. mentioned

00:33:46.640 --> 00:33:48.160
if I forget something,

00:33:48.160 --> 00:33:52.390
Whitesburg had a
pretty strong economy.

00:33:52.390 --> 00:33:56.720
It had U.S. Steel,
RC Cola, Coca Cola.

00:33:56.720 --> 00:33:58.540
Am I forgetting anything
else big?

00:33:58.540 --> 00:34:00.680
&gt;&gt; Herb E. Smith: The
schools are the biggest

00:34:00.680 --> 00:34:01.980
employers probably.

00:34:01.980 --> 00:34:03.280
&gt;&gt; Alexander Gibson:
The schools.

00:34:03.280 --> 00:34:06.820
And you know, all that except
for schools is gone now.

00:34:06.820 --> 00:34:09.610
And Appalshop is still there.

00:34:09.610 --> 00:34:13.840
Coal, you know, was the
largest employer in the region

00:34:13.840 --> 00:34:17.980
and the largest moneymaking
force in the state.

00:34:17.980 --> 00:34:21.440
In that part of the
country, in fact.

00:34:21.440 --> 00:34:23.890
And had incredible
political power.

00:34:23.890 --> 00:34:26.250
Still has incredible
political power everywhere

00:34:26.250 --> 00:34:28.350
that mining still occurs.

00:34:28.350 --> 00:34:31.420
And Appalshop the, you
know, plunky artists

00:34:31.420 --> 00:34:35.480
that don't really impact
the economy, quote unquote,

00:34:35.480 --> 00:34:38.510
grew while everything
else shrank.

00:34:38.510 --> 00:34:41.880
And I think there's some
reasons why that's the case.

00:34:41.880 --> 00:34:44.670
And some of them are
wrapped up in the founding.

00:34:44.670 --> 00:34:49.840
And so, two I think, interesting
elements came together.

00:34:49.840 --> 00:34:55.100
One if the kind of -- the nature
of Appalachian folks as well

00:34:55.100 --> 00:34:57.340
as people of low
income everywhere to try

00:34:57.340 --> 00:35:01.460
and scrap together what you
need to get the job done.

00:35:01.460 --> 00:35:06.320
And that maybe duct tape, it
may be you fix your own thing.

00:35:06.320 --> 00:35:07.940
You make your own widget.

00:35:07.940 --> 00:35:13.560
It may be buying widgets
from D.C. Hitchhiking up here

00:35:13.560 --> 00:35:17.740
to raise money like Herb
E. did some years ago.

00:35:17.740 --> 00:35:20.520
And the other thing was the
background of the founder.

00:35:20.520 --> 00:35:21.820
The first person.

00:35:21.820 --> 00:35:24.860
Bill Richardson came down from
Yale, he was an architect.

00:35:24.860 --> 00:35:29.540
That's an interesting background
to come into film making.

00:35:29.540 --> 00:35:33.470
And at the architecture school
at Yale he was introduced

00:35:33.470 --> 00:35:35.480
to the importance
of other art forms.

00:35:35.480 --> 00:35:37.080
Radio, photography.

00:35:37.080 --> 00:35:38.900
He had to take these courses.

00:35:38.900 --> 00:35:40.850
He had to integrate
that into his work

00:35:40.850 --> 00:35:42.880
in the architecture school.

00:35:42.880 --> 00:35:46.520
And so then Apple shop started
as a, like we mentioned,

00:35:46.520 --> 00:35:50.540
a documentary film workshop
meant to document and talk about

00:35:50.540 --> 00:35:55.900
and explore the area as well
as provide real job training

00:35:55.900 --> 00:35:57.900
for young people in the
mountains that was different

00:35:57.900 --> 00:36:01.520
than the majority for
what was readily available

00:36:01.520 --> 00:36:04.380
which at the time was cold.

00:36:04.380 --> 00:36:07.330
Well as anybody here
who is involved

00:36:07.330 --> 00:36:11.830
in nonprofit fundraising, you
know that there were cycles.

00:36:11.830 --> 00:36:14.060
You know, there will be
buzzwords that are useful

00:36:14.060 --> 00:36:17.830
for 10 years and then,
like vocational training,

00:36:17.830 --> 00:36:23.310
workforce development,
etc. And these are cycles

00:36:23.310 --> 00:36:26.020
that impact some
arts organizations

00:36:26.020 --> 00:36:28.620
in an existential way, you know.

00:36:28.620 --> 00:36:35.970
If you if you orient yourself
around workforce development

00:36:35.970 --> 00:36:39.200
for whatever ethnic group
or population sector

00:36:39.200 --> 00:36:41.540
that you want to, you know,
could be 10 years from now

00:36:41.540 --> 00:36:43.660
that some new think
tank has decided

00:36:43.660 --> 00:36:44.960
that that's not the way to go.

00:36:44.960 --> 00:36:47.930
Instead you need
technological training

00:36:47.930 --> 00:36:51.290
or something else well
Appalshop and the fact

00:36:51.290 --> 00:36:54.460
that we had this kind of
background meant that,

00:36:54.460 --> 00:36:56.150
you know, we started in '69.

00:36:56.150 --> 00:37:00.410
We added a radio station
not that long after.

00:37:00.410 --> 00:37:01.710
Youth media training.

00:37:01.710 --> 00:37:03.150
I think AMI was the
first, wasn't it?

00:37:03.150 --> 00:37:05.110
It's a youth media training

00:37:05.110 --> 00:37:08.020
where we basically recreated
the Appalshop process

00:37:08.020 --> 00:37:10.200
where you had the
filmmaker come and hand

00:37:10.200 --> 00:37:11.500
out cameras to young people.

00:37:11.500 --> 00:37:14.070
Well we created an
organization with an Appalshop

00:37:14.070 --> 00:37:16.580
to do this same thing
and it's been going now.

00:37:16.580 --> 00:37:18.920
It's still going.

00:37:18.920 --> 00:37:21.980
We added music education,
traditional music education.

00:37:21.980 --> 00:37:26.110
We've had many different
programs over the years.

00:37:26.110 --> 00:37:34.860
And as those cycles of
funding went, we had the,

00:37:34.860 --> 00:37:39.130
this sort of Appalachian
-- it's not --

00:37:39.130 --> 00:37:41.290
again, it's not just Appalachian

00:37:41.290 --> 00:37:42.690
but I'm just describing
a situation

00:37:42.690 --> 00:37:44.850
where people have less income
and they need to figure

00:37:44.850 --> 00:37:47.060
out a way to get things to work.

00:37:47.060 --> 00:37:50.570
Well you know, if our
radio was well funded

00:37:50.570 --> 00:37:53.520
than our radio we try to
partner with our filmmakers

00:37:53.520 --> 00:37:56.120
and do projects like that.

00:37:56.120 --> 00:37:58.130
And so we could survive
funding cycles

00:37:58.130 --> 00:38:00.990
because we were big
enough, we were diversified

00:38:00.990 --> 00:38:02.960
in our portfolio to be able

00:38:02.960 --> 00:38:05.790
to absorb some losses
in the market, right.

00:38:05.790 --> 00:38:09.570
And the rest of the
organization could rise.

00:38:09.570 --> 00:38:12.660
So I think that is pretty
unique about Appalshop

00:38:12.660 --> 00:38:14.620
and how it's been
able to survive.

00:38:14.620 --> 00:38:15.920
I think the other piece is

00:38:15.920 --> 00:38:20.500
that our fundamental
mission is not satisfied

00:38:20.500 --> 00:38:23.990
and it won't be until,
you know --

00:38:23.990 --> 00:38:27.590
so, into into what we
do, like Herb E. said.

00:38:27.590 --> 00:38:32.190
What's the -- what --
how am I doing on time?

00:38:32.190 --> 00:38:34.660
Okay. So baked in -- and
I'm not going to talk

00:38:34.660 --> 00:38:35.960
about slides by the way.

00:38:35.960 --> 00:38:39.140
So just enjoy them
on your own time.

00:38:39.140 --> 00:38:42.320
But baked into our idea is
this idea of ridicule, right.

00:38:42.320 --> 00:38:46.180
It was part -- Herb E. spoke
about it in the past tense

00:38:46.180 --> 00:38:47.480
and of course all of you know

00:38:47.480 --> 00:38:49.500
that that's not a
past tense question.

00:38:49.500 --> 00:38:53.030
We're ridiculed practically
every time we're on television.

00:38:53.030 --> 00:38:55.190
Is just to find some new
way to make the point

00:38:55.190 --> 00:39:01.210
that we are racist or a
misogynist or backward or angry

00:39:01.210 --> 00:39:06.960
about international trade or
immigrants or no one really.

00:39:06.960 --> 00:39:08.260
But in fact we all know,

00:39:08.260 --> 00:39:10.010
all of all of the
educated folks here know

00:39:10.010 --> 00:39:11.990
that all those things
are just silly.

00:39:11.990 --> 00:39:13.960
That there is no
job competition.

00:39:13.960 --> 00:39:15.990
That that's just imaginary.

00:39:15.990 --> 00:39:19.760
That there is no --
again, I grew up on a farm.

00:39:19.760 --> 00:39:26.530
So my background of seeing labor
change is in my actual history.

00:39:26.530 --> 00:39:32.310
So I think that the lack of
communication back and forth

00:39:32.310 --> 00:39:34.150
between these sorts of sectors

00:39:34.150 --> 00:39:40.140
of our society is what gives
rise to the stereotypes.

00:39:40.140 --> 00:39:43.660
And Appalshop has been
focused on addressing

00:39:43.660 --> 00:39:45.050
that for a long time

00:39:45.050 --> 00:39:51.200
and unfortunately there's not
more media that comes out of

00:39:51.200 --> 00:39:55.240
that part of the country and
the problems seem to persist.

00:39:55.240 --> 00:39:59.940
The divide seems to not subside

00:39:59.940 --> 00:40:03.740
and I think our country
suffers for that fact.

00:40:03.740 --> 00:40:07.580
So you know, really baked
into the concept of Appalshop

00:40:07.580 --> 00:40:11.320
to go back to the phrase I
used earlier, is this idea

00:40:11.320 --> 00:40:16.620
of differences in power
and differences in access.

00:40:16.620 --> 00:40:22.860
And so how do you
reset the stage?

00:40:22.860 --> 00:40:24.210
How do you provide that access?

00:40:24.210 --> 00:40:28.580
How do you provide opportunities
to people who, you know,

00:40:28.580 --> 00:40:33.700
wouldn't have the
best museum access,

00:40:33.700 --> 00:40:39.130
or after school programs, or
private schools, or you know,

00:40:39.130 --> 00:40:43.280
what do you do to a
historically ignored population.

00:40:43.280 --> 00:40:49.130
What's the method to amplify?

00:40:49.130 --> 00:40:54.010
And the biggest damage that's
done there is not political,

00:40:54.010 --> 00:40:55.530
it's very personal.

00:40:55.530 --> 00:40:58.080
You know, people
grow up like me.

00:40:58.080 --> 00:40:59.590
Like most people in the region.

00:40:59.590 --> 00:41:02.120
Most young people who grow
up and they hate the region.

00:41:02.120 --> 00:41:04.990
You know, they see the
television and they think

00:41:04.990 --> 00:41:08.560
of themselves through that lens.

00:41:08.560 --> 00:41:12.270
And so part of the work that
we do is to explore that.

00:41:12.270 --> 00:41:14.760
And so you'll see people
at the end of, you know,

00:41:14.760 --> 00:41:16.060
we take young people
and we give them

00:41:16.060 --> 00:41:18.300
that youth media education
program I was discussing

00:41:18.300 --> 00:41:21.500
and you'll see them go
through the process of thinking

00:41:21.500 --> 00:41:23.270
about the region,
debating the region,

00:41:23.270 --> 00:41:24.830
thinking about them they're
placed in the region,

00:41:24.830 --> 00:41:29.430
and then sort of coming to
some sort of cathartic moment

00:41:29.430 --> 00:41:33.450
at the end .So all
these things, you know,

00:41:33.450 --> 00:41:35.260
the problems still persist

00:41:35.260 --> 00:41:41.360
and in a similar way
caused by similar problems.

00:41:41.360 --> 00:41:45.200
And part of Appalshops work, the
final piece that I'll mention

00:41:45.200 --> 00:41:49.480
that I think adds to this
and then I'll pass it back

00:41:49.480 --> 00:41:55.510
over to Herb E., is you know,
a very early understanding

00:41:55.510 --> 00:41:58.170
that our problems
shared commonality

00:41:58.170 --> 00:42:01.500
with poor folks across
the world.

00:42:01.500 --> 00:42:02.800
And particularly, communities

00:42:02.800 --> 00:42:07.240
that where extraction
takes place.

00:42:07.240 --> 00:42:12.000
But it's not it's not limited
to a sort of mineral extraction.

00:42:12.000 --> 00:42:15.830
But it's the idea that in order
for, you know, economic systems

00:42:15.830 --> 00:42:19.780
as we currently understand them
to run, they need to be fueled

00:42:19.780 --> 00:42:25.180
by low cost labor for
minerals that can then turn

00:42:25.180 --> 00:42:28.840
into second order products
in some urban center

00:42:28.840 --> 00:42:31.320
or manufacturing place and
then maybe into a third

00:42:31.320 --> 00:42:33.330
or fourth order product
and sold.

00:42:33.330 --> 00:42:34.630
Well we're the first, right.

00:42:34.630 --> 00:42:36.440
We're the first line in that.

00:42:36.440 --> 00:42:39.960
We're the coal, we're the
timber, we're there --

00:42:39.960 --> 00:42:43.320
and so bauxite in
Jamaica, right.

00:42:43.320 --> 00:42:45.390
Coal and Wales.

00:42:45.390 --> 00:42:47.180
Gold in West Africa.

00:42:47.180 --> 00:42:49.640
Diamonds in Central
and East Africa.

00:42:49.640 --> 00:42:55.700
I mean, the nature of
extractive processes power

00:42:55.700 --> 00:42:59.810
and then the people that extract
is almost identical everywhere.

00:42:59.810 --> 00:43:02.830
And it depends on, you know,
it seems to be the limit

00:43:02.830 --> 00:43:05.870
as what is the company
allowed to get away with

00:43:05.870 --> 00:43:08.170
and that's the point
that they'll go to.

00:43:08.170 --> 00:43:09.840
That seems to be my experience

00:43:09.840 --> 00:43:12.680
and so Appalshop understanding
this kind of commonality,

00:43:12.680 --> 00:43:16.210
put us into a much
bigger partnership pool

00:43:16.210 --> 00:43:22.880
than we otherwise would deserve
given our location, you know.

00:43:22.880 --> 00:43:24.940
So we have partners
all over the world

00:43:24.940 --> 00:43:28.040
of all different ethnic groups.

00:43:28.040 --> 00:43:32.240
And that's really been an
informative process to our work

00:43:32.240 --> 00:43:35.640
and I think has helped to
keep us agile and current.

00:43:35.640 --> 00:43:38.260
And again, I just,
I feel very similar

