00:43:44.440 --> 00:43:45.740
I'm here talking about
stuff that everyone,

00:43:45.740 --> 00:43:48.220
that other people
around me have done.

00:43:48.220 --> 00:43:51.990
And so it's a very
humbling experience to be

00:43:51.990 --> 00:43:53.310
in the presence of people.

00:43:53.310 --> 00:43:57.670
You know, my first encounter
with Appalshop was 16 years old.

00:43:57.670 --> 00:43:59.300
I was at Berea College
in Kentucky

00:43:59.300 --> 00:44:02.990
for a summer program
with Upward Bound.

00:44:02.990 --> 00:44:06.030
And people were so familiar
with this self-hatred

00:44:06.030 --> 00:44:09.010
of the Appalachian young
person that you had --

00:44:09.010 --> 00:44:13.040
we did this entire week of
education on Appalachia.

00:44:13.040 --> 00:44:15.040
And it was, okay, what
does Appalachian mean?

00:44:15.040 --> 00:44:18.040
Let's do a sort of in depth --
let's look at this construct.

00:44:18.040 --> 00:44:19.700
Let's look at the
geographical region

00:44:19.700 --> 00:44:21.470
and does the geography
match the culture

00:44:21.470 --> 00:44:23.520
and so then where's the cultural
region and what are we talking

00:44:23.520 --> 00:44:24.820
about when we talk Appalachia?

00:44:24.820 --> 00:44:27.630
Are we talking about the
New York Appalachian range?

00:44:27.630 --> 00:44:29.040
Are we talking about
the southern parts?

00:44:29.040 --> 00:44:32.460
Are we thought my
Georgia, Birmingham?

00:44:32.460 --> 00:44:33.760
What does this mean?

00:44:33.760 --> 00:44:35.470
What's this concept?

00:44:35.470 --> 00:44:37.550
And so that week was
a sort of deep dive.

00:44:37.550 --> 00:44:41.560
And you could have -- that
week was called something

00:44:41.560 --> 00:44:43.580
like Appalachian
Orientation Week.

00:44:43.580 --> 00:44:46.030
It could have been called
Appalshop Orientation Week

00:44:46.030 --> 00:44:47.330
because it was Appalshop film,

00:44:47.330 --> 00:44:49.800
after Appalshop film,
after Appalshop film.

00:44:49.800 --> 00:44:54.350
And you know, in that region
there's really not a lot else.

00:44:54.350 --> 00:45:00.080
So, like Herb E. said, there's
a lot of negative medium

00:45:00.080 --> 00:45:04.660
and it was the first time in my
life that I was asked to think

00:45:04.660 --> 00:45:08.470
about these complicated
questions about the region.

00:45:08.470 --> 00:45:11.580
And then by doing that, I was
sort of able to go outside

00:45:11.580 --> 00:45:13.450
of myself and look at the region

00:45:13.450 --> 00:45:17.650
as a constructive
part of an economy.

00:45:17.650 --> 00:45:22.100
A constructive part
of an economy.

00:45:22.100 --> 00:45:24.770
That sort of eye opening I
think is what a lot of people go

00:45:24.770 --> 00:45:27.750
through when they go
through Appalshop programs

00:45:27.750 --> 00:45:30.210
or when they're exposed
to our materials.

00:45:30.210 --> 00:45:36.180
It's to think broader
than your background.

00:45:36.180 --> 00:45:41.070
And to explore these really
difficult complex projects

00:45:41.070 --> 00:45:50.030
to tell stories that amplify,
educate folks around us.

00:45:50.030 --> 00:45:54.310
And I'll pass it back to Herb
E. now for the final piece.

00:45:54.310 --> 00:46:03.290
&gt;&gt; Herb E. Smith: I wanted
to just say a word or two

00:46:03.290 --> 00:46:11.700
about the importance of
scholars in our work.

00:46:11.700 --> 00:46:15.650
You grow up in a place and you
know a certain amount of --

00:46:15.650 --> 00:46:18.940
you know, you get some
stuff by osmosis, right.

00:46:18.940 --> 00:46:22.340
You didn't -- you're not going
to learn it from your brothers

00:46:22.340 --> 00:46:25.200
and sisters and cousins
and aunts and uncles

00:46:25.200 --> 00:46:29.020
and grandparents and, you know
just the network of friendship

00:46:29.020 --> 00:46:31.770
and kinship in a given place.

00:46:31.770 --> 00:46:35.890
You found out some
things about a place.

00:46:35.890 --> 00:46:40.310
But then there's a whole bunch
of stuff that you don't know.

00:46:40.310 --> 00:46:43.470
And we began to find out that
there were people who were

00:46:43.470 --> 00:46:47.290
like going back and
reading all these documents.

00:46:47.290 --> 00:46:50.120
Like when the deeds
got signed over,

00:46:50.120 --> 00:46:52.470
and how did the coal
companies ended

00:46:52.470 --> 00:46:56.540
up with the mineral rights,
and how did the building

00:46:56.540 --> 00:46:59.580
of these towns happen, and
who's owning the place.

00:46:59.580 --> 00:47:02.590
And for us, we were like whoa.

00:47:02.590 --> 00:47:06.520
And then there was a guy named
Archie Green you had just

00:47:06.520 --> 00:47:11.030
written a book a few years
earlier called Only a Minor.

00:47:11.030 --> 00:47:15.030
And Archie came into
Whitesburg and he's like sitting

00:47:15.030 --> 00:47:18.520
down with us and
talking about how we had

00:47:18.520 --> 00:47:21.900
to like listen to
those scholars.

00:47:21.900 --> 00:47:23.390
And we were like, "They
don't know nothing.

00:47:23.390 --> 00:47:27.000
They got it all wrong, Archie."

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:29.800
And he's -- Archie says,
"Hold on a second, Herb E..

00:47:29.800 --> 00:47:31.690
Just go slow here."

00:47:31.690 --> 00:47:41.330
And I remember we were visiting
a small college in the region.

00:47:41.330 --> 00:47:43.360
And there was a folklorist
there.

00:47:43.360 --> 00:47:48.340
And the folklore said
something about, "Archie,

00:47:48.340 --> 00:47:53.790
why is it that you're always
intervening in these processes.

00:47:53.790 --> 00:47:56.490
That there's a natural
process that happens

00:47:56.490 --> 00:48:00.030
as traditions change."

00:48:00.030 --> 00:48:03.530
And Art says, "What
are you talking about?"

00:48:03.530 --> 00:48:07.420
And he said, There's two buck
deers fighting in the woods.

00:48:07.420 --> 00:48:10.740
Are you going to take sides
with one or the other?"

00:48:10.740 --> 00:48:14.730
And Archie said, "If the
woods on fire I'm going to go

00:48:14.730 --> 00:48:18.370
out there and try to
put the fire out."

00:48:18.370 --> 00:48:21.300
And that's what we thought
we were we were trying to do.

00:48:21.300 --> 00:48:26.120
We were trying to
put the fire out.

00:48:26.120 --> 00:48:27.940
&gt;&gt;John Fenn: Thank
you very much.

