00:49:43.890 --> 00:49:45.720
&gt;&gt;Alexander Gibson: I
could just say that --

00:49:45.720 --> 00:49:48.960
I mean, I'd be interested
in Ethel and Marty on this.

00:49:48.960 --> 00:49:50.260
What they have to say obviously.

00:49:50.260 --> 00:49:53.620
But you know, our, we just
did a series of programs back

00:49:53.620 --> 00:49:56.640
in New York on the, it
was the 50th anniversary

00:49:56.640 --> 00:50:00.450
of the Heart Cellar Act, which
changed immigration patterns

00:50:00.450 --> 00:50:02.140
in this country in
a fundamental way.

00:50:02.140 --> 00:50:03.750
And I think now almost half

00:50:03.750 --> 00:50:08.160
of Americans can directly
relate their family narratives

00:50:08.160 --> 00:50:10.880
to immigration stories
to that act.

00:50:10.880 --> 00:50:14.910
Which changed immigration from
being basically just from parts,

00:50:14.910 --> 00:50:16.930
certain parts of Western Europe.

00:50:16.930 --> 00:50:19.180
Or if you had family
members who are already

00:50:19.180 --> 00:50:22.900
in this country it
opened up the immigration

00:50:22.900 --> 00:50:27.020
to the hemispheric quota --
new atmospheric quota systems.

00:50:27.020 --> 00:50:30.520
So all of a sudden we're
seeing people come from places

00:50:30.520 --> 00:50:34.190
in large numbers that
you hadn't seen before.

00:50:34.190 --> 00:50:37.950
So like for instance, the
Balkans and then, you know,

00:50:37.950 --> 00:50:39.250
expanding out from there.

00:50:39.250 --> 00:50:40.550
I don't know.

00:50:40.550 --> 00:50:43.690
Ethel and Marty, does that
sort of resonate with you?

00:50:43.690 --> 00:50:47.490
The -- was there something new
going on back in 19, the period,

00:50:47.490 --> 00:50:53.050
the mid sixties, immigration
wise that inspired your work?

00:50:53.050 --> 00:50:54.350
&gt;&gt; Ethel Raim: Absolutely.

00:50:54.350 --> 00:50:55.650
I mean, that was a time.

00:50:55.650 --> 00:51:00.600
1965, the Balkan Art Center,
Ethnic Folk Art Center,

00:51:00.600 --> 00:51:02.420
Center for Traditional
Music and Dance.

00:51:02.420 --> 00:51:07.760
I mean, I totally benefited
from that immigration

00:51:07.760 --> 00:51:10.440
and the work was cut out for us.

00:51:10.440 --> 00:51:15.110
We were working primarily with
first-generation Americans

00:51:15.110 --> 00:51:20.160
who were spectacular
carriers of their traditions.

00:51:20.160 --> 00:51:26.030
Musicians, dancers, I mean,
you went to a community event

00:51:26.030 --> 00:51:31.330
and it was an organism
that was working in concert

00:51:31.330 --> 00:51:35.030
and in synchrony that
was pretty extraordinary

00:51:35.030 --> 00:51:37.730
and that was community.

00:51:37.730 --> 00:51:42.150
And the biggest changes
that I see, really,

00:51:42.150 --> 00:51:44.780
is working with second, third,

00:51:44.780 --> 00:51:49.570
and fourth generation
immigrant population as well

00:51:49.570 --> 00:51:52.780
as new immigration
is still happening.

00:51:52.780 --> 00:51:57.420
And as immigration is one of the
top issues in the world today.

00:51:57.420 --> 00:52:02.200
I mean, the amount of displaced
people and and transference

00:52:02.200 --> 00:52:04.200
and population movement.

00:52:04.200 --> 00:52:07.580
I mean, I don't think we -- I
mean, there was huge movement,

00:52:07.580 --> 00:52:08.880
of course, after World War I.

00:52:08.880 --> 00:52:12.670
And I don't know how
that compares to that.

00:52:12.670 --> 00:52:17.150
This period of movement
to that but it's huge.

00:52:17.150 --> 00:52:23.380
And people need to be grounded
and be given the opportunity.

00:52:23.380 --> 00:52:26.360
And so issues of access are

00:52:26.360 --> 00:52:29.240
across both of our
organizations.

00:52:29.240 --> 00:52:32.280
Access, power structure, I mean,
one of the things that Martin

00:52:32.280 --> 00:52:34.930
and I always talked
about was, you know,

00:52:34.930 --> 00:52:39.700
there were no immigrant
artists on TV, you know,

00:52:39.700 --> 00:52:42.660
or in concerts or anywhere.

00:52:42.660 --> 00:52:48.070
And so we didn't -- many, many
concerts, and concert series,

00:52:48.070 --> 00:52:50.730
and tours of concerts,
and festivals.

00:52:50.730 --> 00:52:56.640
And lo and behold, 20 years
later, BAM has ethnic arts,

00:52:56.640 --> 00:52:59.270
and the immigrant arts,
and Lincoln Center,

00:52:59.270 --> 00:53:02.340
and Carnegie Hall, and
it's wonderful, you know.

00:53:02.340 --> 00:53:05.150
So that -- we were the
incubator, so to speak.

00:53:05.150 --> 00:53:06.450
Or the catalyst.

00:53:06.450 --> 00:53:07.890
Both actually.

00:53:07.890 --> 00:53:12.850
And other institutions became
responsive and carried forward.

00:53:12.850 --> 00:53:14.800
But it's still going
to be an issue.

00:53:14.800 --> 00:53:18.750
And again, it's how to work
with immigrant populations

00:53:18.750 --> 00:53:20.990
that are now in third
and fourth generation.

00:53:20.990 --> 00:53:24.770
That's one of the major
issues that I see, and change.

00:53:25.900 --> 00:53:29.600
&gt;&gt; Martin Koenig: Well if I
can just piggyback on that.

00:53:29.600 --> 00:53:35.270
And I must say, when we first
started receiving our grants

00:53:35.270 --> 00:53:41.250
from NEA, Appalshop
was always referred to.

00:53:41.250 --> 00:53:44.010
And an Appalshop
would always be spoken

00:53:44.010 --> 00:53:46.020
about in the same sentence

00:53:46.020 --> 00:53:48.910
that the Balkan Art
Center is spoken about.

00:53:48.910 --> 00:53:52.930
And hearing you speak.

00:53:52.930 --> 00:53:54.690
I'm very moved.

00:53:54.690 --> 00:53:58.680
Because your mission
was our mission.

00:53:58.680 --> 00:54:06.080
As Ethel spoke, we didn't
see ourselves on TV.

00:54:07.220 --> 00:54:09.980
We didn't hear our
music on the radio.

00:54:09.980 --> 00:54:11.280
And that's very difficult now

00:54:11.280 --> 00:54:14.840
because now you've got
world music, the ethnic pop.

00:54:14.840 --> 00:54:21.070
You've got all these forms out
that's very fashionable to go

00:54:21.070 --> 00:54:24.770
into a club and you hear
music from around the world.

00:54:24.770 --> 00:54:29.790
But in 1960's America,
we weren't there.

00:54:29.790 --> 00:54:32.720
We knew that immigrants
built this country

00:54:32.720 --> 00:54:37.170
but immigrant music was not --
there was no exposure to it.

00:54:37.170 --> 00:54:44.330
And if timing is everything,
we benefited from the timing

00:54:44.330 --> 00:54:47.870
of the bicentennial
coming up in 1976.

00:54:47.870 --> 00:54:50.240
So the federal government
was putting money out there

00:54:50.240 --> 00:54:53.800
to have a big party to
celebrate ourselves.

00:54:53.800 --> 00:54:58.330
And the Smithsonian was
supported and was given a budget

00:54:58.330 --> 00:55:04.700
to prepare this great
celebration of our greatness.

00:55:04.700 --> 00:55:07.610
And today it's a
very different world.

00:55:07.610 --> 00:55:10.990
And I don't know where
it's going, quite frankly.

00:55:10.990 --> 00:55:14.420
It's -- I'm totally
confused by it.

00:55:14.420 --> 00:55:17.040
Well I don't think
I'm the only one.

00:55:17.040 --> 00:55:25.800
I would also like to say that
we've been a distant supporter,

00:55:25.800 --> 00:55:27.100
if I could say the word.

00:55:27.100 --> 00:55:32.860
I just always admired what
work you all have done.

00:55:32.860 --> 00:55:35.630
And you know, it's a
big country out there.

00:55:35.630 --> 00:55:39.740
And there's -- even within
the Appalachian region,

00:55:39.740 --> 00:55:44.100
there's a lot of diversity that
doesn't go recognized often.

00:55:44.100 --> 00:55:46.860
And you know, these
mining towns,

00:55:46.860 --> 00:55:49.720
they have all kinds
of people in them.

00:55:49.720 --> 00:55:55.120
And some sense that there's
this remote enclave of people

00:55:55.120 --> 00:55:58.690
who are somehow not a part
of the rest of the country.

00:55:58.690 --> 00:56:01.080
I think, you know, you just

00:56:01.080 --> 00:56:06.790
at some point realize how
completely wrong it is.

00:56:06.790 --> 00:56:12.730
These ideas about who we are and
the places that we're a part of.

00:56:12.730 --> 00:56:17.500
So I think -- another thing I
wanted to mention for us was

00:56:17.500 --> 00:56:25.930
that we also saw it
as a economic task

00:56:25.930 --> 00:56:33.710
that we weren't just
about making films

00:56:33.710 --> 00:56:36.280
or supplying a certain,
you know.

00:56:36.280 --> 00:56:39.790
We ended up with radio station,
theatre company, and so forth.

00:56:39.790 --> 00:56:44.680
And -- but we thought
that if we were going

00:56:44.680 --> 00:56:50.870
to revitalize the homeland, that
we had to model best practices.

00:56:50.870 --> 00:56:59.410
And that today, we have about
a million dollars in payroll

00:56:59.410 --> 00:57:04.890
in a town of 2,000,
2,500 people.

00:57:04.890 --> 00:57:08.680
And it shows up on
the map in Whiteburg.

00:57:08.680 --> 00:57:13.930
And to us, that's really, really
important because it's not

00:57:13.930 --> 00:57:16.280
that we're going to lie.

00:57:16.280 --> 00:57:18.240
It's a plant in the
coal industry.

00:57:18.240 --> 00:57:24.210
But we can figure out ways
to live in those mountains

00:57:24.210 --> 00:57:31.290
and not be subservient
to those powerful forces.

00:57:31.290 --> 00:57:34.460
&gt;&gt; John Fenn: So picking
up on this theme of change.

00:57:34.460 --> 00:57:36.140
I'm going to jump one
of the other questions.

00:57:36.140 --> 00:57:38.820
And again, you've each sort
of addressed this somewhat,

00:57:38.820 --> 00:57:41.080
especially with the
community music initiatives.

00:57:41.080 --> 00:57:44.070
But how is it each organization
integrated community

00:57:44.070 --> 00:57:46.340
perspectives into
documentation projects

00:57:46.340 --> 00:57:47.730
and cultural programming
initiatives?

00:57:47.730 --> 00:57:50.970
So not just necessarily
presenting them representing

00:57:50.970 --> 00:57:52.960
them, but hearing feedback
from the communities

00:57:52.960 --> 00:57:56.540
and the constituents
who are working with

00:57:56.540 --> 00:58:01.710
and then rolling with it?

00:58:01.710 --> 00:58:03.010
&gt;&gt; Alexander Gibson: Okay.

00:58:03.010 --> 00:58:06.090
Well, all of our
programs at Center

00:58:06.090 --> 00:58:07.390
for Traditional Music and Dance.

00:58:07.390 --> 00:58:14.620
I mean, all are really
based in creating a process

00:58:14.620 --> 00:58:17.880
for a dialogue to happen
between the organization,

00:58:17.880 --> 00:58:21.520
and different immigrant
communities, or you know,

00:58:21.520 --> 00:58:23.610
whatever sort of community
we're dealing with.

00:58:23.610 --> 00:58:26.190
Usually immigrant in
ethnic communities.

00:58:26.190 --> 00:58:31.550
And so for most of our projects
we have, you know, we jump --

00:58:31.550 --> 00:58:35.470
we don't just jump in with
programs of documentation.

00:58:35.470 --> 00:58:37.670
We're doing, you
know, eight months

00:58:37.670 --> 00:58:39.290
to a year of field research.

00:58:39.290 --> 00:58:41.400
So folks on our staff,

00:58:41.400 --> 00:58:45.250
or we work with consulting
folklorists,

00:58:45.250 --> 00:58:48.940
and people who have done
work in the community.

00:58:48.940 --> 00:58:51.650
You know, we -- that's
usually the --

00:58:51.650 --> 00:58:54.890
the way we find out
about what's emerging

00:58:54.890 --> 00:58:56.190
in different communities.

00:58:56.190 --> 00:59:00.270
And you know, as well as a lot
of research, you know, with,

00:59:00.270 --> 00:59:02.540
you know, looking at, you know
what the New York Times is

00:59:02.540 --> 00:59:05.110
reporting on different
communities, looking at census,

00:59:05.110 --> 00:59:07.050
statistics, and things
like that.

00:59:07.050 --> 00:59:09.250
Finding out from our friends
what new restaurants are

00:59:09.250 --> 00:59:11.220
out in Jackson Heights
and things like that

00:59:11.220 --> 00:59:14.220
that we should go check out.

00:59:14.220 --> 00:59:18.220
But you know, it's really, you
know, we're spending a good deal

00:59:18.220 --> 00:59:22.130
of time, really, you know, diet,
you know, ultimately meeting

00:59:22.130 --> 00:59:23.430
with community members.

00:59:23.430 --> 00:59:24.990
Interviewing them.

00:59:24.990 --> 00:59:26.800
Finding out what's
important to them.

00:59:26.800 --> 00:59:29.140
Finding out, you know,
what scholarships been done

00:59:29.140 --> 00:59:30.940
on a particular community.

00:59:30.940 --> 00:59:32.360
And then once that's --

00:59:32.360 --> 00:59:35.260
that sort of baseline
research has happened,

00:59:35.260 --> 00:59:37.120
we create project committees.

00:59:37.120 --> 00:59:40.180
So we've had these community
cultural initiatives now we've

00:59:40.180 --> 00:59:43.270
rebranded them as program
called Sustaining Cultures

00:59:43.270 --> 00:59:46.950
but it's very, you know, on
the same theme where we're --

00:59:46.950 --> 00:59:49.940
we have a -- bring together
groups of anywhere from eight

00:59:49.940 --> 00:59:53.420
to 12 community members
who are meeting regularly.

00:59:53.420 --> 00:59:57.070
And so the curation of the
programs, the identification

00:59:57.070 --> 00:59:59.670
of what needs to be
documented and how it needs

00:59:59.670 --> 01:00:01.620
to be documented
and disseminated.

01:00:01.620 --> 01:00:02.920
That's really coming --

01:00:02.920 --> 01:00:04.220
it's coming from the
community members

01:00:04.220 --> 01:00:05.720
and we provide a toolkit.

01:00:05.720 --> 01:00:08.670
We -- because we've done
this work in, you know, 15,

01:00:08.670 --> 01:00:13.100
20 different ethnic communities
and so we have a, you know,

01:00:13.100 --> 01:00:17.010
a track record and know how
about the things that work.

01:00:17.010 --> 01:00:19.920
And how to get funding
for it of course.

01:00:19.920 --> 01:00:21.780
And -- but they're really
telling us, you know,

01:00:21.780 --> 01:00:23.870
how to kind of direct
those resources.

01:00:23.870 --> 01:00:25.970
And that's the -- I mean,
that's what's wonderful

01:00:25.970 --> 01:00:28.620
and the greatest
pleasure of the work.

01:00:28.620 --> 01:00:31.210
I mean, our you know,
when we put on a concert,

01:00:31.210 --> 01:00:33.190
the concert is just
the tip of the iceberg.

01:00:33.190 --> 01:00:38.380
It's really what underpins that
is often years of research years

01:00:38.380 --> 01:00:41.770
of building relationships
with community members.

01:00:41.770 --> 01:00:45.420
And you know, and Marty
and Ethel and I often talk,

01:00:45.420 --> 01:00:47.990
you know, some of the some
of the musicians that Marty

01:00:47.990 --> 01:00:51.500
and Ethel were working back in
the late 60's and early 70's.

01:00:51.500 --> 01:00:53.980
We're working with the
grandchildren of those musicians

01:00:53.980 --> 01:00:57.200
who are now great musicians
and artists in their own right.

01:00:57.200 --> 01:00:59.150
So to have that sort

01:00:59.150 --> 01:01:02.450
of longitudinal
inter-generational dialogue

01:01:02.450 --> 01:01:03.750
about, you know,

01:01:03.750 --> 01:01:09.050
with communities it's what
makes the work so, I think,

01:01:09.050 --> 01:01:13.110
so important, so rooted in the
expressions of the community.

01:01:13.110 --> 01:01:16.640
And just such a pleasure
to work with, you know,

01:01:16.640 --> 01:01:21.250
as a folk arts professional
working in this field.

01:01:21.250 --> 01:01:22.550
So.

01:01:22.550 --> 01:01:23.850
&gt;&gt; Martin Koenig: Well one of
the things that I would say is

01:01:23.850 --> 01:01:26.540
that Appalshop is largely
an organization of people

01:01:26.540 --> 01:01:28.280
