01:03:03.800 --> 01:03:08.910
&gt;&gt; Alexander Gibson: And
the community piece is very

01:03:08.910 --> 01:03:11.840
important in Appalshop's
background in history,

01:03:11.840 --> 01:03:17.050
given coal was the, you
know, a big force --

01:03:17.050 --> 01:03:21.070
you know, I'm trying to
think of a good metaphor.

01:03:21.070 --> 01:03:22.530
Elephant in the blah,
blah, blah.

01:03:22.530 --> 01:03:23.830
You know, you get the point.

01:03:23.830 --> 01:03:25.130
It was big.

01:03:25.130 --> 01:03:26.430
It's big, and important,
and powerful .

01:03:26.430 --> 01:03:30.010
And it was the context
for a lot of our work.

01:03:30.010 --> 01:03:34.200
And you know, that sort of
thing as well as growing

01:03:34.200 --> 01:03:37.440
up the color I am and
the place I grew up,

01:03:37.440 --> 01:03:41.180
made me think quite a bit about
the concepts of community.

01:03:41.180 --> 01:03:43.290
And that's sort of what I
meant when I was saying,

01:03:43.290 --> 01:03:45.030
how do you draw Appalachia?

01:03:45.030 --> 01:03:49.580
Right? It's an interesting
question.

01:03:49.580 --> 01:03:52.860
Are the coal companies
part of our community?

01:03:52.860 --> 01:03:55.550
You know, we've integrated
their perspectives.

01:03:55.550 --> 01:03:59.330
It doesn't mean that we
agree with their perspectives

01:03:59.330 --> 01:04:00.940
and that's true across
the board.

01:04:00.940 --> 01:04:02.330
So and you know, is racism part

01:04:02.330 --> 01:04:04.000
of our cultural heritage
in Appalachia?

01:04:04.000 --> 01:04:08.810
Yes. I would say it's also true
in D.C. but that being said,

01:04:08.810 --> 01:04:10.890
it's part of our
cultural heritage.

01:04:10.890 --> 01:04:13.680
Women leading and and women
being kept from leadership.

01:04:13.680 --> 01:04:15.840
Both of which are part
of our cultural heritage.

01:04:15.840 --> 01:04:19.930
And we'll have people that
we work with who hold beliefs

01:04:19.930 --> 01:04:21.340
that we don't necessarily
agree with.

01:04:21.340 --> 01:04:25.500
And our question -- the
challenge for us always is,

01:04:25.500 --> 01:04:27.260
okay if we're going to
address a particular topic,

01:04:27.260 --> 01:04:30.060
we're to pretend that
these people don't exist.

01:04:30.060 --> 01:04:32.770
And further, we're not going
to create a documentary

01:04:32.770 --> 01:04:36.430
where the purpose is to be God

01:04:36.430 --> 01:04:37.820
and tell you what to
think and believe.

01:04:37.820 --> 01:04:40.620
Nor are we going to
make a documentary

01:04:40.620 --> 01:04:42.430
that ridicules our own people.

01:04:42.430 --> 01:04:44.380
So how do you do
all those things?

01:04:44.380 --> 01:04:49.870
How do you get a sympathetic
coal position into a piece

01:04:49.870 --> 01:04:52.150
without cutting them up and
making them look foolish

01:04:52.150 --> 01:04:54.600
and then creating a piece
that's honest to the region.

01:04:54.600 --> 01:04:57.340
Maybe doing that is what creates
the honesty to the region.

01:04:57.340 --> 01:04:59.030
Maybe not having the voice
over telling you what

01:04:59.030 --> 01:05:00.810
to think is what
creates the honesty.

01:05:00.810 --> 01:05:04.240
But all of these artistic
questions are asked

01:05:04.240 --> 01:05:06.370
because of the democratic
questions underneath.

01:05:06.370 --> 01:05:09.010
Because what we're
doing here is democracy.

01:05:09.010 --> 01:05:11.020
That's what we see
ourself, as participating

01:05:11.020 --> 01:05:12.680
in a fundamental
piece of democracy

01:05:12.680 --> 01:05:15.210
and that's what we see the --

01:05:15.210 --> 01:05:16.840
the reason that we
were created was

01:05:16.840 --> 01:05:19.610
because something was broken.

01:05:19.610 --> 01:05:25.170
And community is just
really, it's really tough --

01:05:25.170 --> 01:05:27.540
it's one of the reasons I
didn't want to not answer any

01:05:27.540 --> 01:05:29.780
of these questions but
it's a tough one for me

01:05:29.780 --> 01:05:34.460
because I don't know whether I
think community is an arbitrary

01:05:34.460 --> 01:05:40.060
line we draw or whether it's
something that's immovable

01:05:40.060 --> 01:05:45.080
yet -- you know, is the Bronx a
distinct community from Queens

01:05:45.080 --> 01:05:46.710
or is it one particular street.

01:05:46.710 --> 01:05:49.720
I mean, at what point -- if
you're Irish were you part

01:05:49.720 --> 01:05:51.660
of it -- were you always part
of it and people just didn't

01:05:51.660 --> 01:05:56.410
like it or -- so those are
difficult questions for me.

01:05:56.410 --> 01:06:00.560
But there's no doubt that the
whatever community is it's

01:06:00.560 --> 01:06:01.860
fundamental to what we do.

01:06:01.860 --> 01:06:04.520
And that's a very
awkward phraseology

01:06:04.520 --> 01:06:08.050
but we an Appalshop will debate
these questions all the time.

01:06:08.050 --> 01:06:09.350
What is our community?

01:06:09.350 --> 01:06:11.560
What's our obligations
to our community?

01:06:11.560 --> 01:06:13.570
Yeah. Sounds like we're
the same organization.

01:06:13.570 --> 01:06:15.340
We just do.

01:06:15.340 --> 01:06:17.230
&gt;&gt; Martin Koenig: It's
variations on the theme.

01:06:17.230 --> 01:06:19.010
&gt;&gt; John Fenn: But it's
a large network, yeah.

01:06:19.010 --> 01:06:20.310
&gt;&gt; Alexander Gibson: Yeah.

01:06:20.310 --> 01:06:22.910
&gt;&gt; John Fenn: Okay I'll pitch
just one more framing question

01:06:22.910 --> 01:06:25.390
then maybe see what
things haven't come

01:06:25.390 --> 01:06:28.020
up that you guys have
been listening to.

01:06:28.020 --> 01:06:30.290
So the futures has come
up a little bit here.

01:06:30.290 --> 01:06:34.800
Looking ahead ,what do you see
as the kinds of programming,

01:06:34.800 --> 01:06:39.320
documentation projects, training
projects your organization

01:06:39.320 --> 01:06:40.620
should be pursuing?

01:06:40.620 --> 01:06:43.570
So if we're looking ahead for
the next 10 years or 50 years,

01:06:43.570 --> 01:06:45.620
you know, you can choose
your own time frame.

01:06:45.620 --> 01:06:49.290
But I know Ethel's hit on some
things like the changing nature

01:06:49.290 --> 01:06:51.750
of demographics and
my great, you know,

01:06:51.750 --> 01:06:53.260
immigration patterns
is something key.

01:06:53.260 --> 01:06:54.690
But what are some other things

01:06:54.690 --> 01:06:57.300
that either organization is
looking at right now coming

01:06:57.300 --> 01:07:02.060
out of this sort of 50
year-ish celebration?

01:07:02.060 --> 01:07:06.490
&gt;&gt; Peter Rushefsky: Back to me.

01:07:06.490 --> 01:07:07.790
All right.

01:07:07.790 --> 01:07:09.090
I'll take it.

01:07:09.090 --> 01:07:11.570
Which reminds me actually,
Ethel always, you know, says,

01:07:11.570 --> 01:07:15.680
poses the question, you have
two ways to learn to operate

01:07:15.680 --> 01:07:18.530
in the present in your own
present and plan for the future.

01:07:18.530 --> 01:07:20.890
One is, you can forget the past

01:07:20.890 --> 01:07:23.290
or you could actually
learn about the past.

01:07:23.290 --> 01:07:27.430
And that doesn't mean you
live your present and build

01:07:27.430 --> 01:07:29.680
to your future in a
backwards looking way

01:07:29.680 --> 01:07:32.020
but you can use an informed way.

01:07:32.020 --> 01:07:36.570
And we find that that
creates a rich creativity

01:07:36.570 --> 01:07:39.130
to draw upon for the future.

01:07:39.130 --> 01:07:40.840
So I think the things

01:07:40.840 --> 01:07:44.410
that what's wonderful are
the things about, that Ethel

01:07:44.410 --> 01:07:48.220
and Marty and other folks,
you know, like at Appalshop

01:07:48.220 --> 01:07:50.790
who built these organizations
at across the country.

01:07:50.790 --> 01:07:54.180
Folk arts organizations like us.

01:07:54.180 --> 01:07:58.210
They built the process
that that grows and changed

01:07:58.210 --> 01:08:00.050
like the U.S. Constitution.

01:08:00.050 --> 01:08:01.730
You know, the things
you hear about that.

01:08:01.730 --> 01:08:06.320
But it really is a process
and a model that, you know,

01:08:06.320 --> 01:08:08.810
it's very malleable
into the future.

01:08:08.810 --> 01:08:11.760
So I mean CTMD will
continue to do a lot

01:08:11.760 --> 01:08:14.010
of field research
in communities.

01:08:14.010 --> 01:08:18.130
We will continue to create
dialogue with communities,

01:08:18.130 --> 01:08:21.150
community members and that
dialogue might be involved

01:08:21.150 --> 01:08:23.180
different technologies
and things like that

01:08:23.180 --> 01:08:24.520
but we're still going
to be talking.

01:08:24.520 --> 01:08:27.500
Okay. We're still going to
be doing public programs.

01:08:27.500 --> 01:08:30.650
We're still going to be doing
documentation of those programs

01:08:30.650 --> 01:08:33.210
and finding ways,
innovative ways

01:08:33.210 --> 01:08:35.520
to disseminate that
documentation.

01:08:35.520 --> 01:08:40.400
You know, in ways that, you
know, serves the community

01:08:40.400 --> 01:08:44.270
and serves the goal of creating
inter community dialogue

01:08:44.270 --> 01:08:45.570
and things like that.

01:08:45.570 --> 01:08:46.870
So I don't know.

01:08:46.870 --> 01:08:49.950
I think it's sort of,
it's hard to project.

01:08:49.950 --> 01:08:52.940
I mean a lot of what we do is,
you know, we plan, you know,

01:08:52.940 --> 01:08:54.730
and Maureen and I, we plan

01:08:54.730 --> 01:08:56.980
or have planning
meetings all the time

01:08:56.980 --> 01:08:59.890
and then something happens in
the world and, you know, we're,

01:08:59.890 --> 01:09:03.190
you know, riding the tides
that everybody else is.

01:09:03.190 --> 01:09:05.480
But you know, I think there's
going to be we'll continue

01:09:05.480 --> 01:09:07.680
to do more and more
partnerships with small

01:09:07.680 --> 01:09:09.230
and community based
organizations.

01:09:09.230 --> 01:09:11.270
Some of those organizations
we may have started 20,

01:09:11.270 --> 01:09:15.370
30 years ago and they've created
their own independent paths.

01:09:15.370 --> 01:09:18.350
And others are, you
know, newly emerging.

01:09:18.350 --> 01:09:23.450
I think, you know, with
technology there's, you know,

01:09:23.450 --> 01:09:25.940
new and better ways to
engage with community members

01:09:25.940 --> 01:09:28.000
and the general public.

01:09:28.000 --> 01:09:32.620
New ways to disseminate
archival materials.

01:09:32.620 --> 01:09:34.710
And you know, with especially
getting back a little bit

01:09:34.710 --> 01:09:37.340
to archives because I
think that's why we're

01:09:37.340 --> 01:09:38.640
here originally.

01:09:38.640 --> 01:09:43.050
It's you know, there's, I think,
when you're creating archives

01:09:43.050 --> 01:09:46.570
and documentation it's always
important to think about,

01:09:46.570 --> 01:09:49.080
well who's the audience
of those materials?

01:09:49.080 --> 01:09:51.200
What's going to be the purpose
of those materials, you know?

01:09:51.200 --> 01:09:53.670
How do you want the audience
member -- and what are the,

01:09:53.670 --> 01:09:56.050
I guess the most -- how do
you make them accessible

01:09:56.050 --> 01:09:57.350
in the easiest way.

01:09:57.350 --> 01:09:59.620
So our boards been talking.

01:09:59.620 --> 01:10:02.120
I'm thinking about that
alongside, you know,

01:10:02.120 --> 01:10:05.080
increasing conversations
with our board about how

01:10:05.080 --> 01:10:08.900
to get more sophisticated
about segmenting

01:10:08.900 --> 01:10:11.140
and targeting particular
audiences.

01:10:11.140 --> 01:10:15.070
Finding better ways to create
programs and documentation

01:10:15.070 --> 01:10:19.020
that would serve maybe
more targeted portions

01:10:19.020 --> 01:10:20.520
of the audience.

01:10:20.520 --> 01:10:23.860
And you know, defining
audiences is always interesting.

01:10:23.860 --> 01:10:27.760
It's you know, we're serving
community based audiences and,

01:10:27.760 --> 01:10:30.310
you know, and there's a
whole diverse spectrum

01:10:30.310 --> 01:10:31.740
of folks within communities.

01:10:31.740 --> 01:10:34.480
And well, as we're
trying to create programs

01:10:34.480 --> 01:10:37.100
that cross bridges
into the general public

01:10:37.100 --> 01:10:38.930
or across to other communities.

01:10:38.930 --> 01:10:41.620
I mean, I think Marty and Ethel
have always talked about some

01:10:41.620 --> 01:10:43.650
of the best projects
and programs

01:10:43.650 --> 01:10:45.250
that we've done in our history.

01:10:45.250 --> 01:10:47.700
Our programs where half the
audience is from the community

01:10:47.700 --> 01:10:49.310
and the other half
is from outside.

01:10:49.310 --> 01:10:52.110
Because for the community
members, they get a sense

01:10:52.110 --> 01:10:55.030
of validation that all these
outside folks are interested

01:10:55.030 --> 01:10:57.660
in what we do and
in our narratives.

01:10:57.660 --> 01:11:02.090
And for the outsiders, it's a
great way when you critical mass

01:11:02.090 --> 01:11:03.850
of community insiders.

01:11:03.850 --> 01:11:05.930
I mean, then you can
really get a window

01:11:05.930 --> 01:11:09.780
of how the traditions the,
whether performing arts

01:11:09.780 --> 01:11:12.610
or whatever arts,
really fit into a context

01:11:12.610 --> 01:11:14.060
within that community.

01:11:14.060 --> 01:11:17.280
So that's a great
balance to look at.

01:11:17.280 --> 01:11:20.080
But you know, I think, I mean,
looking even farther down.

01:11:20.080 --> 01:11:22.720
I mean, I think, there's some
really interesting things

01:11:22.720 --> 01:11:26.150
with media technology,
augmented reality.

01:11:26.150 --> 01:11:28.750
I mean, you know, now we have
the technology and some of,

01:11:28.750 --> 01:11:31.180
a lot of you probably have apps
on your phone where if you hold

01:11:31.180 --> 01:11:34.470
up your cell phone to
something being played

01:11:34.470 --> 01:11:37.080
over a head it can
actually identify the song.

01:11:37.080 --> 01:11:40.830
Well you know, it doesn't go, it
doesn't take too much to connect

01:11:40.830 --> 01:11:42.890
that to -- well you can put
lyrics attached to that.

01:11:42.890 --> 01:11:45.650
So if you're watching a
performance of Albanian music

01:11:45.650 --> 01:11:49.980
in a club and, you know,
in the Bronx or Tirana.

01:11:49.980 --> 01:11:52.160
You can hold up your
cell phone and all

01:11:52.160 --> 01:11:53.670
of a sudden get a
live translation

01:11:53.670 --> 01:11:55.540
of the lyrics and
things like that.

01:11:55.540 --> 01:11:57.020
There's all sorts
of, you know --

01:11:57.020 --> 01:11:58.950
or get bios of the
performers just

01:11:58.950 --> 01:12:01.630
from hearing their voice
and things like that.

01:12:01.630 --> 01:12:05.200
So there's going to be a lot of
interesting ways that, I think,

01:12:05.200 --> 01:12:09.010
live programming and
documentation are going

01:12:09.010 --> 01:12:12.130
to get more and more
integrated in the future.

01:12:12.130 --> 01:12:15.870
And through, you know,
different media technologies.

01:12:15.870 --> 01:12:19.300
And this this stuff is not
very far away, you know.

01:12:19.300 --> 01:12:21.640
And people are already
thinking about this.

01:12:21.640 --> 01:12:25.600
&gt;&gt; John Fenn: What do you
guys think about the future?

01:12:25.600 --> 01:12:26.900
&gt;&gt; Alexander Gibson:
Unfortunate --

01:12:26.900 --> 01:12:30.900
so there's two things I could
politician my way out of this

01:12:30.900 --> 01:12:33.880
and answer a different
question than the one was asked.

01:12:33.880 --> 01:12:35.210
I could say ditto
because I agree

01:12:35.210 --> 01:12:37.870
with everything that
was just said.

01:12:37.870 --> 01:12:41.100
But I'll take the third which
I think is just add a couple

01:12:41.100 --> 01:12:42.400
other things.

01:12:42.400 --> 01:12:45.690
But everything he said I
agree with, I think is true.

01:12:45.690 --> 01:12:49.070
I think with Appalshop, you
know, our mission is not

01:12:49.070 --> 01:12:52.640
yet satisfied and
is still strong.

01:12:52.640 --> 01:12:55.520
It's still applicable,
as applicable today

01:12:55.520 --> 01:12:57.600
as it was when it started.

01:12:57.600 --> 01:13:02.070
And that's sad in a lot
of ways but expected.

01:13:02.070 --> 01:13:06.610
Again, we're just now getting
out of the coal industry which,

01:13:06.610 --> 01:13:10.880
you know, politically
marginalizes those that extract

01:13:10.880 --> 01:13:14.380
because you need to keep
the cost as low as possible.

01:13:14.380 --> 01:13:17.310
So you know, we may
see a new horizon

01:13:17.310 --> 01:13:18.750
of Appalachia coming forward.

01:13:18.750 --> 01:13:20.810
I don't know that that's true.

01:13:20.810 --> 01:13:23.080
I hope that it is.

01:13:23.080 --> 01:13:24.910
Economically is what I mean.

01:13:24.910 --> 01:13:27.310
And Herb E. and I, we're looking

01:13:27.310 --> 01:13:31.550
over the questions before
we came and I was thinking,

01:13:31.550 --> 01:13:33.780
you know, seems to
me the only way

01:13:33.780 --> 01:13:37.560
that our mission would no longer
-- would need to be revised --

01:13:37.560 --> 01:13:40.490
or perhaps Appalshop would
need to close because all

01:13:40.490 --> 01:13:43.930
of our staff would not
be oriented in this way.

01:13:43.930 --> 01:13:46.630
Would be if Appalachia somehow,

01:13:46.630 --> 01:13:49.410
let's say kudzu is this
is this invasive crop.

01:13:49.410 --> 01:13:53.430
Let's say kudzu turns
into this delicious wine

01:13:53.430 --> 01:13:59.670
that everyone loves and
now -- so if Appalachia,

01:13:59.670 --> 01:14:03.740
if that region turned in a
Napa Valley economically,

01:14:03.740 --> 01:14:07.460
the context for our work
would be gone, you know,

01:14:07.460 --> 01:14:10.960
because of course someone
living in a winery in that part

01:14:10.960 --> 01:14:12.440
of the country can
hire their own media

01:14:12.440 --> 01:14:14.500
and tell their own story
and other people want

01:14:14.500 --> 01:14:17.220
to tell their stories.

01:14:17.220 --> 01:14:18.740
So it's fundamentally
about the piece.

01:14:18.740 --> 01:14:20.780
It's about being
politically invisible.

01:14:20.780 --> 01:14:24.980
Politically marginalized, low
income, and all the effects

01:14:24.980 --> 01:14:26.870
and issues that come with that.

01:14:26.870 --> 01:14:29.460
So that's really
central to how we think

01:14:29.460 --> 01:14:32.280
about our work and
that may change.

01:14:32.280 --> 01:14:37.270
Again, we're all hopeful that
it will change but there's

01:14:37.270 --> 01:14:41.070
so many barriers at the moment.

01:14:41.070 --> 01:14:43.650
And so we try our best
and I'm really hopeful

01:14:43.650 --> 01:14:49.360
with this new generation of
young people coming up that are,

01:14:49.360 --> 01:14:52.170
again, that may be that
may always be true.

01:14:52.170 --> 01:14:55.800
But really politically engaged.

01:14:55.800 --> 01:15:00.400
Not as interested in
questions of race and religion.

01:15:00.400 --> 01:15:03.270
And they're more interested
in doing work and trying

01:15:03.270 --> 01:15:07.400
to create the place that
they want to live in.

01:15:07.400 --> 01:15:11.050
So, you know, we just try
to provide the best road

01:15:11.050 --> 01:15:14.600
to that destination we can at
Appalshop for the young people

01:15:14.600 --> 01:15:17.420
that -- for the most number
of young people that we can.

01:15:17.420 --> 01:15:20.620
And it's really -- it's
-- you know, it's --

01:15:20.620 --> 01:15:22.280
there's not a lot of
competition in that area,

01:15:22.280 --> 01:15:24.990
which is good for
our fundraising.

01:15:24.990 --> 01:15:30.020
It's bad for the state, for
the effect that we're seeking.

01:15:30.020 --> 01:15:31.320
Yeah.

01:15:31.320 --> 01:15:33.050
&gt;&gt; I want to turn it
over to some questions

01:15:33.050 --> 01:15:34.350
from the audience now.

01:15:34.350 --> 01:15:35.930
We have a little bit of time
here to take any as well

01:15:35.930 --> 01:15:38.300
as if you guys have questions
that sort of come up,

01:15:38.300 --> 01:15:39.600
we can pitch those as well.

01:15:39.600 --> 01:15:41.040
And there are microphones
that are going to be walking

01:15:41.040 --> 01:15:42.470
around so we can make sure

01:15:42.470 --> 01:15:45.320
that the questions are
captured on the video.

01:15:45.320 --> 01:15:46.790
&gt;&gt; So yeah.

01:15:46.790 --> 01:15:52.490
I think across the spectrum,
you mentioned the mockery

01:15:52.490 --> 01:15:57.760
and the stereotyping, and I know
that was true for my culture,

01:15:57.760 --> 01:16:02.000
Yiddish language was just
the stuff of buffoonery.

01:16:02.000 --> 01:16:07.330
How do you deal generationally
with the internalized shame

01:16:07.330 --> 01:16:13.160
of generation one wanting
to transform their children

01:16:13.160 --> 01:16:18.090
into sort of vanilla,
you know, whatever,

01:16:18.090 --> 01:16:20.820
and distance themselves
from their own culture?

01:16:20.820 --> 01:16:22.810
And I know what you're
talking about.

01:16:22.810 --> 01:16:27.720
What you're doing is the
affirming and the validation,

01:16:27.720 --> 01:16:32.050
but you almost sometimes have
to fight a generation in order

01:16:32.050 --> 01:16:34.500
to get that to happen.

01:16:34.500 --> 01:16:36.240
So that's my question.

01:16:36.240 --> 01:16:38.120
How do you do that?

01:16:38.120 --> 01:16:39.420
Or what do you think about that?

01:16:39.420 --> 01:16:40.720
&gt;&gt; Herb E. Smith: Well,
I think it's the --

01:16:40.720 --> 01:16:46.570
I think it's the deepest, most
enduring challenge that we have

01:16:46.570 --> 01:16:52.080
in Appalachian region today,
is how we free ourselves

01:16:52.080 --> 01:16:54.560
from this internalized
oppression.

01:16:54.560 --> 01:16:58.130
And the sense of
having to apologize

01:16:58.130 --> 01:17:01.740
for who your people are,
how you dress, how you talk,

01:17:01.740 --> 01:17:08.160
how your family makes a living
or maybe draws food stamps

01:17:08.160 --> 01:17:13.410
or whatever it takes to
survive in those mountains.

01:17:13.410 --> 01:17:20.400
Often, there's, with
the survival,

01:17:20.400 --> 01:17:25.230
a sense of failure often.

01:17:25.230 --> 01:17:28.320
And I want to get past that.

01:17:28.320 --> 01:17:29.620
I really do.

01:17:29.620 --> 01:17:34.070
I think this sense
of -- I think what --

01:17:34.070 --> 01:17:39.650
if there is a consistent goal
for 50 years at Appalshop,

01:17:39.650 --> 01:17:43.480
it's trying to deal with that.

01:17:45.070 --> 01:17:51.670
&gt;&gt; I have a question also
for Herb E. I'm wondering,

01:17:51.670 --> 01:17:57.260
what brought the American Film
Institute to Whitesburg in 1969?

01:17:57.260 --> 01:18:00.540
I think George Stevens
Jr. was the head of AFI.

01:18:00.540 --> 01:18:02.350
I don't know that he had
a particular interest.

01:18:02.350 --> 01:18:05.480
I'm also wondering whether
the Whitesburg Eagle.

01:18:05.480 --> 01:18:09.230
It screams, you know, that
was well known at the time.

01:18:09.230 --> 01:18:13.960
Did that have anything to do
with why AFI chose Whitesburg?

01:18:13.960 --> 01:18:15.260
&gt;&gt; Herb E. Smith: Yeah.

01:18:15.260 --> 01:18:17.590
Actually, community
film works --

01:18:17.590 --> 01:18:21.100
the AFI [inaudible] community
film workshop Council,

01:18:21.100 --> 01:18:25.130
they basically chose
Appalachian one of their places.

01:18:25.130 --> 01:18:27.810
At first they didn't choose
Whitesburg but you're right.

01:18:27.810 --> 01:18:29.750
The fact that the
Gish's were there and had

01:18:29.750 --> 01:18:36.060
that amazing newspaper
was a huge factor in Bill

01:18:36.060 --> 01:18:39.550
and Josephine deciding
to move to Whitesburg.

01:18:39.550 --> 01:18:46.120
But I think the --
in the larger sense,

01:18:46.120 --> 01:18:53.070
I think there was a
realization that we are

01:18:53.070 --> 01:18:56.510
in this large diverse country

01:18:56.510 --> 01:18:59.180
that we aren't always
recognizing

01:18:59.180 --> 01:19:05.090
and that we had a lot
of work to do in terms

01:19:05.090 --> 01:19:11.300
of documenting the realities
of life in eastern Kentucky

01:19:11.300 --> 01:19:13.480
and southwestern
Virginia and that

01:19:13.480 --> 01:19:14.990
that central Appalachian region.

01:19:14.990 --> 01:19:21.120
So I think there was an
acknowledgement of that need

01:19:21.120 --> 01:19:25.020
that ended up meaning that
people would locate that.

01:19:25.020 --> 01:19:27.670
I don't think the
impetus was from AFI.

01:19:27.670 --> 01:19:32.070
I think what was happening with
AFI was that they were applying

01:19:32.070 --> 01:19:34.370
for funding from the National
Endowment for the Arts

01:19:34.370 --> 01:19:40.440
and they needed to show
a more diverse activity

01:19:40.440 --> 01:19:48.930
than basically the AFI
staff were, you know,

01:19:48.930 --> 01:19:54.640
reflected the reality behind
the cameras at that time,

01:19:54.640 --> 01:19:58.450
which was this very
narrow range of people

01:19:58.450 --> 01:20:00.620
in the country being represented

01:20:00.620 --> 01:20:02.460
in the production
side of things.

01:20:02.460 --> 01:20:04.320
And so AFI realized in order --

01:20:04.320 --> 01:20:06.970
if you're going to keep getting
federal dollars, you're going

01:20:06.970 --> 01:20:10.930
to have to train some
different people to assume some

01:20:10.930 --> 01:20:18.120
of the roles in producing
media in this country.

01:20:18.120 --> 01:20:23.150
&gt;&gt; Marty mentioned that
at one time at NEA,

01:20:23.150 --> 01:20:27.350
the two organizations you
represent were often mentioned

01:20:27.350 --> 01:20:28.650
in the same sentence.

01:20:28.650 --> 01:20:31.600
And the reality is there
were very few not-for-profits

01:20:31.600 --> 01:20:35.000
at that time and that
was indeed the case.

01:20:35.000 --> 01:20:38.420
Something that hadn't been
brought up but I think

01:20:38.420 --> 01:20:40.750
that was a factor
is that at NEA,

01:20:40.750 --> 01:20:44.820
Amy Spelman started an expansion
arts program there and they --

01:20:44.820 --> 01:20:47.990
it was mainly to serve
communities of color first

01:20:47.990 --> 01:20:52.120
and then expanded to
serve rural organizations.

01:20:52.120 --> 01:20:53.750
So that was a factor.

01:20:53.750 --> 01:20:56.770
And then at NEA, the
advancement program

01:20:56.770 --> 01:21:00.210
and the challenge program
both were put in place

01:21:00.210 --> 01:21:07.430
to help organizations develop
and develop funding as well.

01:21:07.430 --> 01:21:11.290
Those programs have
disappeared today

01:21:11.290 --> 01:21:13.740
and I wondered what your
thinking is in terms

01:21:13.740 --> 01:21:15.670
of funding sources

01:21:15.670 --> 01:21:18.300
for infrastructure today
for not-for-profits.

01:21:18.300 --> 01:21:25.000
Where do you find your money and
what funding streams are there

01:21:25.000 --> 01:21:29.940
or not today when you're
looking for support?

01:21:29.940 --> 01:21:35.170
&gt;&gt; Peter Rushefsky: I'm the
guy who still wears a tie.

01:21:35.170 --> 01:21:36.490
Yeah. No. Barry, right on.

01:21:36.490 --> 01:21:41.620
I mean, so much of the sort
of support that was, you know,

01:21:41.620 --> 01:21:45.910
either for general operations
or, you know, for infrastructure

01:21:45.910 --> 01:21:49.750
like the challenge grants helped
us establish a New York Cultural

01:21:49.750 --> 01:21:51.830
Heritage Fund, which is
not a huge endowment,

01:21:51.830 --> 01:21:54.160
but at least we have, you
know, some money in the bank.

01:21:54.160 --> 01:21:55.460
Go ahead, Ethel.

01:21:55.460 --> 01:21:56.910
&gt;&gt; Ethel Raim: Barry was talking
about something even earlier

01:21:56.910 --> 01:21:59.520
which was the institutional
advancement grant

01:21:59.520 --> 01:22:02.690
which was so crucial.

01:22:02.690 --> 01:22:07.020
We had Peggy Delaney
working with us

01:22:07.020 --> 01:22:09.000
and talking about,
what are the goals?

01:22:09.000 --> 01:22:11.370
What does the organization
look like in ten years?

01:22:11.370 --> 01:22:12.670
What are you needs?

01:22:12.670 --> 01:22:15.520
I mean, and that was 1979,

01:22:15.520 --> 01:22:20.010
and then the first private
foundation support we got was

01:22:20.010 --> 01:22:23.590
in '84 from Ford Foundation
because there was someone

01:22:23.590 --> 01:22:25.950
who was interested in
what we were doing.

01:22:25.950 --> 01:22:27.250
But, Pete, keep going.

01:22:27.250 --> 01:22:28.550
&gt;&gt; Peter Rushefsky: Yeah.

01:22:28.550 --> 01:22:30.650
And that was Lynn
[inaudible] who supported both.

01:22:30.650 --> 01:22:33.770
&gt;&gt; Also funded Appalshop.

01:22:33.770 --> 01:22:35.070
Lynn [inaudible]

01:22:35.070 --> 01:22:36.370
&gt;&gt; Peter Rushefsky:
Lynn continues

01:22:36.370 --> 01:22:37.670
to be on our board too.

01:22:37.670 --> 01:22:38.970
So but right.

01:22:38.970 --> 01:22:40.270
And so, I mean, so much

01:22:40.270 --> 01:22:42.600
of the funding now is really
project-based funding,

01:22:42.600 --> 01:22:45.850
and it makes it very tough
when you're, you know,

01:22:45.850 --> 01:22:47.880
spinning through a whole
bunch of different, you know,

01:22:47.880 --> 01:22:51.380
projects to make sure that
there's enough money carved

01:22:51.380 --> 01:22:56.590
out of those, you know, those
not -- never enough grants to,

01:22:56.590 --> 01:22:59.300
you know, support operations,
support the development

01:22:59.300 --> 01:23:02.650
of the organization, support
things like your website,

01:23:02.650 --> 01:23:07.120
support, you know, your office,
you know, whatever support staff

01:23:07.120 --> 01:23:08.420
and things like that

01:23:08.420 --> 01:23:11.080
and building an archive
until tomorrow.

01:23:11.080 --> 01:23:13.400
So it's -- you know, it's --

01:23:13.400 --> 01:23:15.640
that's the sort of
conversation we have

01:23:15.640 --> 01:23:18.100
with funders all
the time but it's --

01:23:18.100 --> 01:23:20.210
you know, I think our field --

01:23:20.210 --> 01:23:23.630
I think public folklore in
general could do a better job,

01:23:23.630 --> 01:23:27.520
I think, representing
itself as a field

01:23:27.520 --> 01:23:28.820
to the funding community.

01:23:28.820 --> 01:23:31.430
I think there's a lot of funders
who really don't know what folk

01:23:31.430 --> 01:23:34.330
and traditional arts
are really all about.

01:23:34.330 --> 01:23:40.630
So I know, you know, NEA is one
great advocate I think we have

01:23:40.630 --> 01:23:44.850
to, I think, getting the
word out about, you know,

01:23:44.850 --> 01:23:46.150
what the what the field does.

01:23:46.150 --> 01:23:48.970
And Cliff has, you know,
been carrying on that

01:23:48.970 --> 01:23:50.270
that message very well.

01:23:50.270 --> 01:23:51.770
But it's something
we need to keep --

01:23:51.770 --> 01:23:55.140
continue to work on
and I think really kind

01:23:55.140 --> 01:24:00.890
of get a wider community of
funders to understand not just,

01:24:00.890 --> 01:24:04.380
you know, not just -- there's
an urgency to the work because,

01:24:04.380 --> 01:24:07.050
you know, a lot of times
we're dealing with traditions

01:24:07.050 --> 01:24:10.320
or that may not be around in
another generation unless work

01:24:10.320 --> 01:24:12.550
is done in partnership
with the communities

01:24:12.550 --> 01:24:16.350
that have helped them
preserve the work --

01:24:16.350 --> 01:24:20.750
preserve the artistic
work that they do.

01:24:22.170 --> 01:24:23.470
&gt;&gt; Martin Koenig: You
know, after being married

01:24:23.470 --> 01:24:26.590
to this organization for so many
years, I finally got married

01:24:26.590 --> 01:24:32.190
to a person and it
altered my life.

01:24:32.190 --> 01:24:35.490
And, ultimately, what
often happens was I got --

01:24:35.490 --> 01:24:39.910
I have three children
and twins came along,

01:24:39.910 --> 01:24:43.040
and anyone who knows
anything about twins, I mean,

01:24:43.040 --> 01:24:46.220
you're underwater until
they get old enough.

01:24:46.220 --> 01:24:50.790
And my wife agreed to have
children if I would spend 50%

01:24:50.790 --> 01:24:53.790
of my time bringing them up.

01:24:53.790 --> 01:24:56.220
She wasn't going to
do it by herself.

01:24:56.220 --> 01:25:00.490
So I left the organization
about 25 years ago,

01:25:00.490 --> 01:25:05.610
and once my kids got old enough,
I have gotten back into the work

01:25:05.610 --> 01:25:10.150
and I'm working with
the Smithsonian in terms

01:25:10.150 --> 01:25:12.460
of doing some publishing
of material

01:25:12.460 --> 01:25:17.340
that I had recorded separately
in those first five years

01:25:17.340 --> 01:25:23.640
when Margaret Mead supported
the work that I was doing.

01:25:23.640 --> 01:25:26.720
So here I am approaching 80

01:25:26.720 --> 01:25:31.370
and I forgot what I was
about to talk about.

01:25:31.370 --> 01:25:36.730
I didn't mean to --
oh, I know what it is.

01:25:36.730 --> 01:25:39.230
Okay. One of the
problems, folks.

01:25:39.230 --> 01:25:44.540
So I live on an island
off of Seattle,

01:25:44.540 --> 01:25:51.030
and to do this work now, for
Folkways, I have to raise money.

01:25:51.030 --> 01:25:55.420
And I made a little 501c3
organization not to burden them

01:25:55.420 --> 01:25:59.410
with taking on an additional
thing of what I'm doing

01:25:59.410 --> 01:26:03.100
from the other side
of the country.

01:26:03.100 --> 01:26:07.060
I am fundraising in a
totally different way.

01:26:07.060 --> 01:26:10.680
&gt;&gt; Ethel Raim: It was so
much in my life and not

01:26:10.680 --> 01:26:12.980
in the rest of the world, right?

01:26:12.980 --> 01:26:16.040
So that was a huge motivation.

01:26:16.040 --> 01:26:20.390
You know, and when people start
writing my bios now, they say,

01:26:20.390 --> 01:26:23.320
she was at a meeting at
the Newport Foundation

01:26:23.320 --> 01:26:26.800
and she said it was a wonderful
festival but I didn't hear any

01:26:26.800 --> 01:26:28.500
of the accents that
she grew up with,

01:26:28.500 --> 01:26:30.500
that I grew up with,
and it's true.

01:26:30.500 --> 01:26:36.220
I didn't. You know, so that was
a big piece of my motivation,

01:26:36.220 --> 01:26:39.830
was to really get that kind
of representation and get

01:26:39.830 --> 01:26:42.480
that access for those
communities that was

01:26:42.480 --> 01:26:47.310
so hidden and now less hidden.

01:26:47.310 --> 01:26:50.210
&gt;&gt; I said something
pretty quick.

01:26:50.210 --> 01:26:56.330
I had occasion to travel into
some coal mines in Russia,

01:26:56.330 --> 01:27:02.670
and what I noticed was
that it was like the 1950s

01:27:02.670 --> 01:27:05.000
in those Russian coal mines.

01:27:05.000 --> 01:27:08.260
And what became clear
was there was no dissent.

01:27:08.260 --> 01:27:13.160
There was nobody challenging
the coal industry in Russia

01:27:13.160 --> 01:27:15.850
to change their practices.

01:27:15.850 --> 01:27:20.550
They would send 2,000 people
into a Russian coal mine

01:27:20.550 --> 01:27:24.320
and we would send 200 people
and we would mine more

01:27:24.320 --> 01:27:26.280
than those 2,000 Russian miners.

01:27:26.280 --> 01:27:27.730
I said, "What do
they do all day?

01:27:27.730 --> 01:27:29.030
They had the same equipment."

01:27:29.030 --> 01:27:35.450
And they said, "Well we
-- everybody needs a job."

01:27:35.450 --> 01:27:38.280
But, you know, at some point,
you don't want to send everybody

01:27:38.280 --> 01:27:41.780
into an underground coal mine
just because they need a job,

01:27:41.780 --> 01:27:44.320
so I think this idea

01:27:44.320 --> 01:27:50.500
of challenging the prevailing
powers-that-be is really,

01:27:50.500 --> 01:27:55.660
really important as we deal
with the realities of a place

01:27:55.660 --> 01:27:57.540
that is facing hard times.

01:27:57.540 --> 01:28:02.340
&gt;&gt; Is it a short
question, Cliff?

01:28:02.340 --> 01:28:04.520
&gt;&gt; Cliff: I'll make it short.

01:28:04.520 --> 01:28:05.820
&gt;&gt; Okay.

01:28:05.820 --> 01:28:08.420
&gt;&gt; Cliff: So [inaudible] I'd
love just to say congratulations

01:28:08.420 --> 01:28:11.020
to Ethel on receiving the
National Heritage Fellowship

01:28:11.020 --> 01:28:13.510
and I --

01:28:13.510 --> 01:28:17.830
[ Applause ]

01:28:17.830 --> 01:28:21.010
And in watching the
slideshow, seeing the number

01:28:21.010 --> 01:28:23.930
of National Heritage fellows
that you've advocated,

01:28:23.930 --> 01:28:25.270
that your organization
has advocated

01:28:25.270 --> 01:28:27.330
for over the years
really is a testament

01:28:27.330 --> 01:28:32.270
to your incredible work
on behalf of others.

01:28:32.270 --> 01:28:35.210
So thank you for that.

01:28:35.210 --> 01:28:38.590
I would say, you
know, just to add

01:28:38.590 --> 01:28:40.890
to what Barry Burgee
mentioned earlier,

01:28:40.890 --> 01:28:45.550
people still name-check CTMD
and Appalshop at the NEA

01:28:45.550 --> 01:28:47.710
when they're talking
about organizations

01:28:47.710 --> 01:28:50.400
that they aspire
to be like, right?

01:28:50.400 --> 01:28:51.700
In the traditional arts.

01:28:51.700 --> 01:28:58.020
And it gets me thinking, you
know, I wonder 50 years in,

01:28:58.020 --> 01:29:01.020
right, you could -- if you
were a building, you could be

01:29:01.020 --> 01:29:03.820
on the National Register
of Historic Places.

01:29:03.820 --> 01:29:06.510
&gt;&gt; Herb E. Smith: I don't
want to be a building.

01:29:06.510 --> 01:29:07.810
&gt;&gt; Cliff: So right.

01:29:07.810 --> 01:29:12.860
So how is it -- right, see,
there must be a perception.

01:29:12.860 --> 01:29:14.810
If people name check you,
they have a perception

01:29:14.810 --> 01:29:17.130
of what your organization
is all about in how you work

01:29:17.130 --> 01:29:19.040
and who you represent
and how you do it.

01:29:19.040 --> 01:29:21.500
And I imagine you must face that
in the communities that you work

01:29:21.500 --> 01:29:23.760
in and have been
working in for so long.

01:29:23.760 --> 01:29:25.940
So how do you stay nimble?

01:29:25.940 --> 01:29:31.260
How do you keep your identity
from ossifying in a way

01:29:31.260 --> 01:29:33.940
that enables you to work
with so many different types

01:29:33.940 --> 01:29:35.760
of people and perspectives?

01:29:35.760 --> 01:29:37.500
Is that a short question?

01:29:37.500 --> 01:29:39.250
&gt;&gt; Yes but the answer is long.

01:29:39.250 --> 01:29:44.330
&gt;&gt; I mean, you know I said it's
come up in a couple of her ways

01:29:44.330 --> 01:29:46.420
and you guys, but
they both hit on it.

01:29:46.420 --> 01:29:48.750
The founders established a
process for working the people

01:29:48.750 --> 01:29:51.030
and I think that process has
allowed agility is what I've

01:29:51.030 --> 01:29:53.500
been hearing across the panels.

01:29:53.500 --> 01:29:55.690
And so it's not like you
set out with the blueprint

01:29:55.690 --> 01:29:57.180
if you're just going to
do this and you do it

01:29:57.180 --> 01:29:58.480
through thick or thin.

01:29:58.480 --> 01:29:59.780
You -- is that it?

01:29:59.780 --> 01:30:01.080
&gt;&gt; Peter Rushefsky:
Right, right.

01:30:01.080 --> 01:30:02.380
Well, I mean, luckily
there's been no shortage

01:30:02.380 --> 01:30:05.410
of new communities moving to
New York City and great artists

01:30:05.410 --> 01:30:08.750
that nobody knows that
may be driving taxis

01:30:08.750 --> 01:30:12.810
or working restaurant shifts
late at night or tending bar or,

01:30:12.810 --> 01:30:16.540
you know, doing what we've got,
you know, wonderful artists

01:30:16.540 --> 01:30:19.180
who are grave diggers
during the day.

01:30:19.180 --> 01:30:23.450
And so anytime we start worrying
about that, we just open

01:30:23.450 --> 01:30:26.930
up our eyes and ears realize
that there's just new --

01:30:26.930 --> 01:30:29.710
more and more folks who
are continuing to come

01:30:29.710 --> 01:30:32.000
to the country, coming
to the city.

01:30:32.000 --> 01:30:35.110
But, you know, also, you know,
the organizations are adapting.

01:30:35.110 --> 01:30:38.210
I mean, some of the
artists we work with now,

01:30:38.210 --> 01:30:41.480
they're way more sophisticated
with social media than we --

01:30:41.480 --> 01:30:43.020
anybody on our staff is.

01:30:43.020 --> 01:30:46.450
I mean, and so I think the
dialogues that get created

01:30:46.450 --> 01:30:49.590
with the artists and the
community members were --

01:30:49.590 --> 01:30:54.340
I mean, they're the most
invigorating thing we can do

01:30:54.340 --> 01:30:57.320
as an organization is just have
those dialogues because it's

01:30:57.320 --> 01:30:59.890
through them that we find
out about great new ways

01:30:59.890 --> 01:31:01.610
that they're applying
their artistry,

01:31:01.610 --> 01:31:04.030
things that are changing
in the communities

01:31:04.030 --> 01:31:06.590
that we never imagined,
you know, how the --

01:31:06.590 --> 01:31:09.330
a lot of the communities
are really --

01:31:09.330 --> 01:31:12.210
it's very much post diasporic,
I guess, or whatever you --

01:31:12.210 --> 01:31:13.860
however you want to call it.

01:31:13.860 --> 01:31:15.530
But there's -- they're
not just --

01:31:15.530 --> 01:31:18.890
they're no longer separated
from their home communities.

01:31:18.890 --> 01:31:20.190
They're very much --

01:31:20.190 --> 01:31:21.490
&gt;&gt; They're transnational.

01:31:21.490 --> 01:31:22.790
&gt;&gt; Peter Rushefsky:

01:31:22.790 --> 01:31:24.090
Transnational and
things like that.

01:31:24.090 --> 01:31:26.750
So I think it's --
I mean, we're --

01:31:26.750 --> 01:31:28.830
as much as we're creating
a lot of these programs,

01:31:28.830 --> 01:31:30.130
we're sort of --

01:31:30.130 --> 01:31:32.460
we're benefiting from the
creativity that's already there

01:31:32.460 --> 01:31:35.500
and already existing in these
communities and we're, you know,

01:31:35.500 --> 01:31:38.110
trying to channel
that into, you know,

01:31:38.110 --> 01:31:40.920
in ways that we hope
serves the community

01:31:40.920 --> 01:31:45.220
and serves the greater
public in creating dialogue.

01:31:45.220 --> 01:31:46.520
&gt;&gt; You guys have something?

01:31:46.520 --> 01:31:47.820
&gt;&gt; Alexander Gibson: Yeah.

01:31:47.820 --> 01:31:49.120
Because of the work
that folks like Herb E.

01:31:49.120 --> 01:31:51.660
and the founders did, you
know, Appalshop, when it puts

01:31:51.660 --> 01:31:54.300
out a call for a new
job, gets applications

01:31:54.300 --> 01:31:55.940
from all over the country.

01:31:55.940 --> 01:32:00.590
And so we were able to get a lot
of people that help diversify

01:32:00.590 --> 01:32:02.700
and rejuvenate our practice.

01:32:02.700 --> 01:32:05.370
One example of that -- and
that's part of the process.

01:32:05.370 --> 01:32:08.100
And the other thing I would say
before I give the example is

01:32:08.100 --> 01:32:09.640
that we've always had
community members.

01:32:09.640 --> 01:32:10.940
We've never had a
professional board.

01:32:10.940 --> 01:32:14.080
It's always been a mix of
workers and community members.

01:32:14.080 --> 01:32:15.930
I think that's been
really important.

01:32:15.930 --> 01:32:23.720
Our current board chair is a
longtime advocate for justice

01:32:23.720 --> 01:32:25.240
in the region and so she --

01:32:25.240 --> 01:32:26.830
and she's also never
worked at Appalshop

01:32:26.830 --> 01:32:29.400
so it's very interesting.

01:32:29.400 --> 01:32:32.250
And her brother is a -- also
works now with Appalshop

01:32:32.250 --> 01:32:35.980
and is very conservative and --

01:32:35.980 --> 01:32:39.030
anyway, so it's always been
an interesting balance.

01:32:39.030 --> 01:32:43.910
So the example I'll give is
that we have a person who came

01:32:43.910 --> 01:32:46.880
and interviewed for a community
development job and his job was

01:32:46.880 --> 01:32:50.090
to go around and
organize basically.

01:32:50.090 --> 01:32:51.730
I didn't give him
the title organizer

01:32:51.730 --> 01:32:54.520
because that title makes me
nervous, but fundamentally,

01:32:54.520 --> 01:32:56.160
that's what he's doing.

01:32:56.160 --> 01:32:59.520
And it's in this context of
wealth and power and control

01:32:59.520 --> 01:33:02.190
and new future and where's
coal and where are we

01:33:02.190 --> 01:33:05.470
and are we deciding and can we
partner in new power structures,

01:33:05.470 --> 01:33:08.380
can we create new
economic linkages?

01:33:08.380 --> 01:33:12.910
So during the interview,
the guy struck me

01:33:12.910 --> 01:33:15.320
as perhaps having
some challenges.

01:33:15.320 --> 01:33:16.830
Now, we had a lot of
interviews for this.

01:33:16.830 --> 01:33:18.370
He came from Connecticut.

01:33:18.370 --> 01:33:19.970
He was very different.

01:33:19.970 --> 01:33:22.640
He had pocket -- he
had things on his --

01:33:22.640 --> 01:33:24.510
elbow patches, you know,
like professors have.

01:33:24.510 --> 01:33:26.820
He had a doctorate
in organizing.

01:33:26.820 --> 01:33:32.810
He quoted Saul Alinsky all the
time and he opens his meetings

01:33:32.810 --> 01:33:35.270
by saying, "I'm a
communist Jew from New York

01:33:35.270 --> 01:33:37.660
and I'm here to work."

01:33:37.660 --> 01:33:39.560
And then when he's
challenged on it, he says,

01:33:39.560 --> 01:33:40.970
"Well, that's not true.

01:33:40.970 --> 01:33:43.730
There are no good communist
parties in Kentucky."

01:33:43.730 --> 01:33:46.160
And he's been incredibly
successful

01:33:46.160 --> 01:33:47.700
as an organizer in the region.

01:33:47.700 --> 01:33:49.000
Incredibly successful.

01:33:49.000 --> 01:33:53.020
I think he's more
well-liked then most anybody

01:33:53.020 --> 01:33:57.090
and by the community, and that's
how he opens up his meetings.

01:33:57.090 --> 01:33:59.180
It's interesting.

01:33:59.180 --> 01:34:03.130
But Appalshop, by, I think,
by continual, you know,

01:34:03.130 --> 01:34:04.430
bringing in new people.

01:34:04.430 --> 01:34:06.270
Like I said, we don't
pay them enough,

01:34:06.270 --> 01:34:08.640
so at some point they
go off somewhere else.

01:34:08.640 --> 01:34:12.130
But that's been the way that
I think we've most been able

01:34:12.130 --> 01:34:15.980
to stay agile is the integration
of new people with new ideas

01:34:15.980 --> 01:34:19.810
and the particular mentality of
Appalachian people which, again,

01:34:19.810 --> 01:34:22.230
if we get in -- if we got into
a big discussion of racism,

01:34:22.230 --> 01:34:23.530
I could go into,

01:34:23.530 --> 01:34:26.340
but fundamentally there's
this kind of, you know,

01:34:26.340 --> 01:34:28.260
you prove yourself
to me through time.

01:34:28.260 --> 01:34:29.560
I can count on you.

01:34:29.560 --> 01:34:32.310
You show up when you say
you're going to show up.

01:34:32.310 --> 01:34:34.530
You're good.

01:34:34.530 --> 01:34:36.780
Versus this this
initial, you know,

01:34:36.780 --> 01:34:38.260
I haven't seen someone
like you before.

01:34:38.260 --> 01:34:40.540
You have things on your pockets.

01:34:40.540 --> 01:34:41.840
You know, now you need to show

01:34:41.840 --> 01:34:43.440
up a couple times
before I trust you

01:34:43.440 --> 01:34:45.700
or maybe your skin's too
dark or maybe you're a woman

01:34:45.700 --> 01:34:47.680
or maybe you're Muslim.

01:34:47.680 --> 01:34:52.450
So these are the challenges
that, you know, that we face,

01:34:52.450 --> 01:34:53.750
but I think that's
how we've been able

01:34:53.750 --> 01:34:56.760
to maintain agility is one
in the structure and then two

01:34:56.760 --> 01:34:58.790
in the recruitment of new
and interesting people

01:34:58.790 --> 01:35:01.340
that bring different approaches.

01:35:01.340 --> 01:35:04.810
&gt;&gt; Herb E. Smith: And I must
say, we did realize as elders

01:35:04.810 --> 01:35:10.630
that we had to stay
out of their way.

01:35:10.630 --> 01:35:14.590
&gt;&gt; Alexander Gibson: Most
of them have realized that.

01:35:14.590 --> 01:35:15.890
Yeah.

01:35:15.890 --> 01:35:17.240
&gt;&gt; Well, on that note,
we're going to get

01:35:17.240 --> 01:35:18.540
out of the way of
the next panelist.

01:35:18.540 --> 01:35:20.340
I want to thank you all.

01:35:20.340 --> 01:35:23.430
[ Applause ]

01:35:23.430 --> 01:35:25.940
And I'm going to suggest we'll
start the next panel five

01:35:25.940 --> 01:35:28.590
minutes later than we planned,
so it'll be like 3:05 just

01:35:28.590 --> 01:35:31.460
to give to people time
to reboot and refresh.

01:35:31.460 --> 01:35:32.760
So thank you very much.

